column168: EMPLOYEE PICKED UP WASTE AT CUSTOMERS LOCATION LOADED ON TRUCK AND PROCEEDED BACK TO FACILITY.  EMPLOYEE PARKED TRUCK IN DESIGNATED AREA AT FACILITY FOR PICKUP OF WASTE OF THE FOLLOWING BUSINESS DAY.  EMPLOYEE WENT INTO FACILITY TO DO HIS PAPER WORK WHEN HE RETURNED TO THE TRUCK APPROX TWENTY MINUTES LATER TO PLACE MANIFESTS ON FRONT SEAT HE NOTICED A LIQUID DRIPPING OUT OF THE CARGO AREA OF TRUCK HE NOTIFIED PROPER PERSONNEL THEN PROCEEDED TO CLEANUP.  SAFETY KLEEN PERSONNEL HELPED TO CLEAN UP SPILL USING CORN COB ABSORBENT TOWELS.  THE SPILL WAS A RESULT OF A LEAKING DRUM ON BACK OF TRUCK CAUSED BY TRANSPORATION OF THE DRUM WITH RUST ON BOTTOM OF DRUM.  ONLY 1/2 GALLON OF WASTE ESCAPED TRUCK ONTO ASPHULT.  APPROX 1 GALLON WAS CONTAINED IN TRUCK.  LEAKING DRUM ALONG WITH SPILLED MATERIAL WERE PLACED IN AN OVER PACK DRUM TO CONTINUE ITS ROUTE TO THE DESIGNATED FACILITY.
LEAKING AT VALVE STEM OF LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE. TIGHTENED PACKING RETAINER BOLTS STOPPING LEAK AND FORE WARDED CAR TO ITS DESTINATION.

column168: THE PORTABLE TANK THAT WAS DAMAGED WAS A PLASTIC BLADDER CONTAINED INSIDE A STEEL FRAME. THE TANK WAS BEING LOADED INTO A TRAILER WHEN A FORK LIFT PUT A CUT IN THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK. THE FORK LIFT BLADE REMAINED IN THE TANK UNTIL THE LEAK WAS CONTAINED. THE TANK WAS TURNED UPSIDE DOWN TO STOP THE LEAK. THE SHIPPER CAME IN THE SAME DAY AND TRANSFERRED THE PRODUCT INTO THE DRUMS. THE DRUMS AND EMPTY TANK WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. ANY SPILLED PRODUCT, AN INDUSTRIAL TYPE SOAP, WAS CLEANED UP WITH OIL DRY. THE EMPLOYEE WAS DISCIPLINED AND REINSTRUCTED TO ONLY MOVE PORTABLE TANKS WITH THE FORKS IN THE RUNNERS PROVIDED ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK.

THREE DRUMS WERE FOUND APPARENTLY LEAKING FROM THE BUNG HOLES. THE SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED AS INSTRUCTED AND THE DAMAGED PORTION OF THE SHIPMENT SEALED INSIDE RECOVERY DRUMS.

column168: ON 5-9-94 CARGO TANK 1155 WAS EMPTY & BEING PURGED WITH WATER BEING PREPARED FOR SALE. APPROX 30 GALS OF COLD WATER WAS INTRODUCED INTO THE TANK. TANK STARTED TO LEAK VAPOR & LIQUID FROM LEFT FRONT CORNER ABOVE THE UPPER 5TH WHEEL PLATE. VAPOR WAS EMITTED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE & LIQUID SPILLED ONTO THE ASPHALT PAVEMENT. PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED ON THE ASPHALT & NO PRODUCT REACHED A WATER OR SEWAGE SYSTEM OR DIRT. THE SPILL OF THE PRODUCT CAUSED THE EVACUATION OF PERSONNEL FORM THE TERMINAL. EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL WERE CALLED THE SITUATION CONTAINED & THE PRODUCT CLEANED UP & PROPERLY DISPOSE OF. CARGO TANK 1155 HAD BEEN PARKED ON TERMINAL LOT & OUT OF SERVICE SINCE 12-90. TANK 1155 WAS BEING PORGED & CLEANED FOR SALE.

DRIVER PICKED UP TANK AND DURING ROUTE NOTICED SOME LEAKING FROM TRAILER. DRIVER STOPPED, LEAKING CONTINUED AND DRIVER CALLED OTTAWA OFFICE WHICH IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED A CLEANUP CREW.  CREW STOPPED LEAKING AND SOAKED UP SPILLED MATERIAL WITH MP 79 AND HAZARD PILLOWS.  WE NOTIFIED LOCAL BUREAU COUNTY LEPC HOWEVER NO ONE SHOWED UP AT THE SCENE.
CONTAINERS WAS STRUCK BY A PALLET OF FREIGHT WHILE LOADING TRAILER.  SMALL HOLE IN DRUM CAUSED BY WOODEN PALLET.  CLEAN UP BY CONTRACTOR IN ACCORDANCE WITH MFG INSTRUCTION.

column168: A 7,500 GALLON STORAGE TANK FOR N-PROPANOL WAS BEING FILLED OFF A TRANSPORT. THE STORAGE TANK CONTAINED 4270 GALLONS PRIOR TO PUMPING. WE ATTEMPTED TO PUMP AN ADDITIONAL 3700 GALLONS INTO THE TANK. UPON REACHING ITS CAPACITY, THE TANK OVERFILLED AND PRODUCT SPILLED OUT AN OVERFLOW VALVE AT THE TOP OF THE TANK. THE TRANSPORT PUMP WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN. THE SPILL WAS ESTIMATED AT APPROX 135 POUNDS (20 GALLONS). THE SPILL WAS ABSORBED USING A SORBENT MATERIAL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE TANK FARM WHICH HAS AN IMPERMEABLE LINING. TRANSPORT UNLOADING PROCEDURES ARE BEING RE-WRITTEN TO HELP PREVENT FUTURE SPILLS OF THIS TYPE AT THIS FACILITY. ALSO, MAXIMUM STORAGE CAPACITY WILL BE NOTED ON EACH TANK NEAR THE TANK'S GAUGE. IMMEDIATE ACTION TAKEN INCLUDES A SPEED LETTER ISSUED TO TRANSPORT UNLOADING PERSONNEL INSTRUCTING THEM TO CHECK WITH OPERATIONS OR OFFICE MANAGER PRIOR TO PUMPING TO MAKE SURE THE LOAD WILL FIT IN TANK.

AFTER HOOK UP WAS MADE DRIVER PUT PUMP IN GEAR AND STARTED TO PUMP OFF PRODUCT.  AFTER PUMPING FOR TWO TO THREE MINUTES WHEN THE PUMP QUIT, THE FRONT U JOINT ON THE PUMP SHAFT HAD BROKEN.  THE DRIVER PUT THE PTO OUT OF GEAR AND GOT UNDER THE TRUCK TO CHECK PUMP SHAFT.  WHILE HE WAS UNDER THE TRUCK THE UNLOADER WHO WAS WITH HIM SAID THAT PRODUCT WAS COMING OUT OF THE TOP OF OUR CARGO TANK.  THEY THEN CLOSED THE STORAGE TANK VALVE AND THE UNLOADING VALVES ON OUR CARGO TANK.  THE STORAGE TANK DID NOT HAVE A CHECK VALVE SO THE PRODUCT FLOWED IN REVERSE THROUGH THE PUMP INTO OUR CARGO TANK AND OVERFLOWED ABOUT 20 GALS.  THE CONSIGNEE WASHED IT DOWN WITH WATER INTO THEIR CLOSED SYSTEM TO THEIR TREATMENT PLANT.

column168: IN RESPONSE TO COMMUNITY INQUIRIES, AN INVESTIGATION WAS MADE BY THE EMPORIA FIRE CHIEF YOUNGKIN TO DETERMINE THE SOURCE OF A REPORTED STENCH. THE CHIEF IDENTIFIED THREE TANKS CARS IN THE ATSF RAIL YARD AS POSSIBLE SOURCES.  AS ONE OF THE CARS WAS PLACARDED FOR A POISON LIQUID, THE CHIEF ORDERED A PRECAUTIONARY EVACUATION OF SIX CITY BLOCKS, OR APPROXIMATELY 200 CITIZENS.  ATSF RESPONDERS ASSESSED THE AREA AND DETERMINED THE RELEASE TO BE FROM A TANK CAR LAST CONTAINING A SOLUTION OF SODIUM SULFIDE.  THE RELEASE WAS FOUND TO BE A COMBINATION OF A DEFECTIVE GASKET AND A LOOSE FITTING.  THE GASKET BETWEEN THE SAFETY VALVE AND TANK CAR TANK FLANGE WAS SUFFICIENTLY DETERIORATED TO PERMIT SEEPAGE OF VAPOR. BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED, SEALER WAS APPLIED AND A WRAP OF PLASTIC WAS INSTALLED; HOWEVER, THE STENCH PERSISTED.  THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE STEM WAS FOUND TO BE LOOSE.  WHEN TIGHTENED THE REMAINDER OF THE RELEASE WAS ELIMINATED.  TEXACO REPRESENTATIVES WERE DISPATCHED THE FOLLOWING DAY TO REPAIR THE GASKET PRIOR TO THE CAR BEING MOVED TO THE PLANT.

DRIVER STATED THAT HE FAILED TO CLOSE UNLOADING VALVE ON THE PREVIOUS LOAD.  WHEN HE ARRIVED TO UNLOAD AT INDIANAPOLIS HE REMOVED THE CAP FROM THE UNLOADING LINE, WENT TO THE TOP OF THE TANK AND HOOKED UP HIS AIR LINE AND STARTED CHARGING HIS TANK WITH AIR TO BLOW OFF THE LOAD.  HE STATED THAT PRODUCT CAME OUT THE UNLOADING LINE RIGHT AWAY DUE TO THE FACT THAT THE VALVE HAD NOT BEEN CLOSED FROM THE PREVIOUS LOAD.  THE PRODUCT, APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS, WAS CONTAINED IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA. CONSIGNEE WASHED INTO THEIR PIT WHICH GOES TO THEIR TREATMENT PLANT.

column168: DRIVER BEGAN VACUUMING PRODUCT INTO TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY NOTICED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM ONE OF THE HOSE FITTINGS. HE QUICKLY TURNED OFF PUMP AND USED THE SPILL KIT FROM HIS TRUCK TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN SPILL. UPON INVESTIGATION THE DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT THE HOSE FITTING WAS NOT CONNECTED PROPERLY WHICH ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO LEAK ONTO THE PAVEMENT. HE REATTACHED THE HOSE PROPERLY AND CONTINUED TO LOAD TANK. THE SPILL WAS LIMITED TO APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS AND REMAINED IN CONTAINMENT ON THE PAVEMENT. THE ABSORBANT SOCKS AND PADS USED IN THE CLEAN-UP OF THE SPILL WERE DISPOSED OF BY THE W.V AIR CENTER. ALL DRIVERS WERE MADE AWARE OF THE INCIDENT AND REMINDED OF THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE HOSES ARE PROPERLY CONNECTED BEFORE LOADING A TANK.

column168: WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE TRANSFER LOCATION (SAFETY KLEEN CORP. IN LEXINGTON, SC), A DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING ON THE TRAILER. SAFETY KLEEN PERSONNEL OVERPACKED THE LEAKING CONTAINER AND CLEANED THE TRAILER FLOOR. ALL CLEANUP DEBRIS WAS PUT INTO DRUMS AND DISPOSED OF ALONG WITH THE LOAD. NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS LOST TO THE ENVIRONMENT OR ENTERED ANY DRAINS OR WATERWAYS.

ON MAY 18, 1994 MY DRIVER BEGAN TO VAC LIQUID INTO THE CARGO TANK. BECAUSE THE MATERIAL WAS SO LIGHT IN WEIGHT THE VACCUUM PRESSURE PULLED THE MATERIAL DIRECTLY THRU THE PRIMARY CUT-OFF VALVE AND THRU THE SECONDARY SCRUBBER. THEN THE FLUID CONTINUED TO BE VACCED THRU THE PUMP ITSELF AND THRU ITS EXHAUST WHERE IT LEAKED TO THE GROUND. ALL OF THE MATERIAL THAT SPILLED WAS CONTAINED IN ENVIRONMENTAL WASTE RESOURCES' SECONDARY CONTAINMENT. THERE WAS NO OTHER CONTAMINATION FROM THE SPILL AND THE CONTAINMENT AREA WAS CLEANED BY ENVIRONMENTAL WASTE RESOURCES' PERSONEL AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS RETURNED TO THE STORAGE TANK. UPON INSPECTION OF OUR TANK IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE FLOAT BALL LOCATED IN THE SECONDARY SCRUBBER WAS CRACKED WHICH PREVENTED IT FROM FLOATING TO THE TOP AND SHUTTING OFF THE PUMP PROPERLY. THE FLOAT BALL WAS REPLACED AND THE CARGO TANK WAS PLACED BACK IN SERVICE. OUR MAINTENANCE PEOPLE WERE INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT THE FLOAT BALLS PERIODICALLY ON ALL TANKS TO INSURE THEY ARE IN WORKING ORDER. WE FEEL THAT THIS PROCEDURE WILL INSURE THAT A REOCCURENCE OF THIS INCIDENT DOES NOT HAPPEN IN THE FUTURE.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0730 ON MAY 20, 1994, A SHIPMENT OF WASTE BEING IMPORTED FROM CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT DE MEXICO, KM. 14.5, CARRETERA ESCENICA, TIJUANA B.C., MEXICO ARRIVED AT CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT, 2301 WEST BROADWAY ROAD, PHOENIX, ARIZONA. CWM-PHOENIX IS A HAZARDOUS WASTE MANAGEMENT ACT. CWM 1704 WEST FIRST STREET, AZUSA, CALIFORNIA WAS THE IMPORTER OF RECORD. THE WASTE WAS SHIPPED ON A UNIFORM HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST, DOCUMENT NUMBER #00770. CHEMICAL DISPOSAL WAS THE TRANSPORTER, AZT050010008. AS THE VEHICLE WAS BEING UNLOADED IT WAS OBSERVED THAT A PLASTIC WOVEN BAG CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE (D039), PROPER SHIPPING NAME: "RQ" WASTE ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, SOLID, N.O.S. (PERCHLOROETHENE), HAD LEAKED MATERIAL ONTO THE FLOORING OF THE CONTAINERS ON THE VEHICLE, IT APPEARED THAT THE BAG HAD RUBBED CONTAINER TO BE BREACHED. THE CONTAINER HAD NOT BEEN MOVED BY CWM-VEHICLE FLOORING. THE RELEASE WAS DISCOVERED AT 0805. LESS THAN 0.5 POUNDS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED. THE RELEASED DID NOT CONSTITUTE A REPORTABLE QUANTITY. FACILITY PERSONNEL DONNED PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, I.E., TYVEK OUTER GARMENT, FULL-FACE RESPIRATOR WITH AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE AND HEPA-FILTER, STEEL-TOED BOOTS AND NITRILE GLOVES. THE MATERIAL ON THE FLOOR OF THE VEHICLE WAS REMOVED AND RETURNED TO THE CONTAINER. THE BREACH IN THE CONTAINER WAS TEMPORARILY SECURED WITH DUCT TAPE. THE CONTAINER WAS REMOVED FROM THE VEHICLE AND PLACED IN AN "OVERPACK" PLASTIC WOVEN BAG. THE VEHICLE FLOORING WAS DECONTAMINATED USING A DETERGENT SOLUTION. THE SOLUTION WAS ABSORBED. THE ABSORBENT WAS PLACED IN THE OVERPACKED CONTAINER FOR MANAGEMENT AS HAZARDOUS WASTE. THE INCIDENT RESPONSE WAS COMPLETED BY 0840. THE SKY WAS CLEAR AND THE TEMPERATURE WAS IN THE MID-EIGHTIES FAHRENHEIT. CWM-PHOENIX CONTACTED THE IMPORTER OF RECORD (CWM-AZUSA) AND INFORMED THEM OF THE INCIDENT. CWM-AZUSA INDICATED THAT THE FOREIGN GENERATOR WOULD BE CONTACTED AND MEASURES IMPLEMENTED TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: ON FRIDAY MAY 13TH, 1994 I PICKED UP A LOAD AT 6:30 A.M. AT ALL PURE TO BE DELIVERED TO RAGING WATERS IN SAN DIMAS, CA. UPON ARRIVAL AT 7:15 A.M. I MET ONE OF THE MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL, I INFORMED HIM WHO I WAS AND WHAT I WAS DELIVERING, THEN HE TOOK ME TO THE TANK LOCATIONS. AFTER SHOWING ME ALL THREE LOCATIONS, I DROVE MY TRUCK TO THE FIRST TANK, I FIRST HAD TO MOVE SEVERAL DESKS AND CHAIRS OUT OF THE WAY SO I COULD MANEUVER AROUND AND BACK MY TRAILER INTO THE FILL LINE. AFTER THAT I WENT TO THE TANKS AND CHECKED THAT ALL THE VALVES WERE OPEN AND ON THE WAY I NOTICED THERE WAS SOME CONSTRUCTION GOING ON NEAR THE FIRST TANK AND THERE WERE SEVERAL MEN WORKING THERE. AFTER GOING BACK TO THE TRUCK I PROCEEDED HOOKING UP MY DISCHARGE HOSE AND HOOKING UP MY AIR. THEN I TURNED ON THE CUSTOMERS FULL LIGHT WARNING SYSTEM, I OPENED THEIR VALVE THEN OPENED MY DISCHARGE VALVE. AFTER SEVERAL MINUTES OF UNLOADING I WAS LOOKING AT THE CONSTRUCTION WORKERS WHEN ONE OF THEM MOTIONED ME WITH HIS HANDS AND SAID THERE WERE SOME LIQUID COMING OUT OF THEIR PIPE; AT THAT MOMENT I STOPPED THE DISCHARGING OF THE LIQUID. CONTACTING THE SUPERVISOR NAME MIKE. AFTER EXPLAINING HIM THE PROBLEM WE GOT EVERYONE OUT OF THE IMMEDIATE AREA. I CONTACTED MY DISPATCHER AND INFORMED HER OF THE SITUATION, SHE TOLD ME THAT SHE WOULD CONTACT THE FIRD DEPT. AND INFORM THEM OF THE SITUATION AND MY LOCATION. AFTER SEVERAL MINUTES THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND I SPOKE TO CAPTAIN HATCH OF THE 64 BATTALION WITH THE LOS ANGELES COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT. AFTER GIVING HIM MY SHIPPING PAPERS AND A COPY OF THE M.S.D.S. OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION, HE ASKED ME IF THE SPILLED HAD BEEN CONTAINED, AND AT THAT MOMENT IT WAS, WHICH THEN HE PROCEEDED VERIFING THAT IT WAS CONTAINED WITH HIS CREW. AT THE TIME HE CONTACTED THE HAZ MAT TEAM. WHEN THE HAZ MAT TEAM ARRIVED THEY TOOK OVER, SOON AFTER THEY FINISHED THEIR INVESTIGATION THEY GAVE CLEARANCE TO RETURN BACK INTO THE IMMEDIATE AREA AND INFORMED US EVERYTHING WAS FINE AND GAVE ME OK TO PROCEED WITH MY WORK. AFTER CHECKING WITH MIKE HE INFORMED ME THAT THEY HAD REPAIRED THEIR PIPE. I THEN TALKED TO BILL CLEVENGER WITH ALL PURE CHEMICAL COMPANY WHICH HE HAD BEEN CALLED BY MY COMPANY AND HAD BEEN THERE APPROXIMATELY AN HOUR, HE INFORMED ME THAT HE WANTED TO CONTINUE WITH FILLING THE CUSTOMERS AND FINISHED FILLING THEIR TANKS WITH OUT ANY OTHER PROBLEMS.

column168: OUR DRIVER LEFT OUR YARD AT 10:45 AM ON 5/24/94 AND WENT TO BUTCHER DIST. WHICH IS ABOUT 8 MILES FROM OUR TERMINAL. WHEN WE DETERMINED WHAT IT WAS WE CALLED INFOTERK TO DETERMINE WHAT TO DO. THEY SAID WE COULD MOVE THE TRAILER AWAY FROM THE BUILDING AND INTO THE STREET AS LONG AS IT WAS NOT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER AND WE DID. WE CALLED THE FIRE DEPT. AND THEY CALLED HAZMAT. AFTER DISCUSSING IT THEY DECIDED TO HAVE US MOVE THE TRAILER BACK TO OUR TERMINAL AND TOLD US TO CONTACT A CLEANUP COMPANY TO COME AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL WHICH WE DID. THEY CAME BY ABOUT 1 HOUR AFTER WE CONTACTED THEM AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL. I HAVE TALKED TO ALL OF THE DRIVERS AND DOCK WORKERS AND INSTRUCTED THEM ON IN THE PROPER WAY TO HANDLE THESE SHIPMENTS IN THE FUTURE.

OUR DRIVER SHOULD HAVE COMPLETED HIS HOOK UP AND OPENED ALL VALVES PRIOR TO PRESURIZING HIS TANK.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR DELIVERY AT DESTINATION. HE PROCEEDED TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE AND AFTER ABOUT 20 MINS. THE RECEIVER TOLD OUR DRIVER TO SHUT DOWN AND THAT THE STORAGE TANK WAS OVERFLOWING. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED IN A MOAT AROUND THE STORAGE TANK. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE GUAGE ON THE TANK WAS INOPERATIVE, GIVING A FALSE READING ON THE AMOUNT OF MATERIAL ALREADY IN STORAGE. THE REMAINDER OF THE MATERIAL WAS UNLOADED AT ANOTHER LOCATION IN THE PLANT.

DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTED TO NEGOIATE A 180 DEGREE HORSEHOSE TYPE TURN ON HWY 136.  IN DOING HE HAD TO TRAVEL OVER INTO THE OPPOSING LANE.  AS HE WAS IN THE TURN HE NOTICED ONCOMING TRAFFIC AND HAD TO STEER BACK INTO HIS LANE SOONER THAN HE PLANNED.  THIS CAUSED THE FIFTH WHEEL TO PIVOT FORWARD ALLOWING THE TRAILER TO LEAN TO THE RIGHT.  ALSO THE RIGHT SIDE TANDEMS LEFT THE ROADWAY WHICH CAUSED THE TRAILER TO LEAN EVEN MORE.  DUE TO THE STEEP GRADE IN THE ROADWAY, THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO PULL THE TRAILER BACK ONTO THE ROADWAY.  THE 3 INCH FITTING ON THE TOP REAR OF TRAILER STARTED LEAKING.  APPROXIMATELY 1/2 PINT OF PRODUCT LOSS.  CLEANED UP BY OHM CORPORATION.

column168: A VACUUM TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM LOMAC, INC. LOCATED AT 5025 EVANSTON AVENUE IN MUSKEGON, MI TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 2900 BROADWAY IN CLEVELAND, OH IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE FRONT DOME HATCH ONTO THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER AND AN ASPHALT LOADING AREA. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH ABSORBANT PADS AND DECONTAMINATED THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER. UPON INSPECTION OF THE DOME HATCH, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE HATCH WAS PROPERLY SECURED.  IT WAS SUSPECTED THAT THE GASKET OF THE HATCH WAS DEFECTIVE WHICH ALLOWED THE PINT OF MATERIAL TO ESCAPE.  PRIOR TO CONTINUING THE TRIP, A NEW GASKET WAS INSTALLED AND THE DOME HATCH SECURED.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE INSPECTED THE VEHICLE AND NO DEFECTS WERE IDENTIFIED. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH VEHICLE PRIOR TO DEPARTURE AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A DEFICIENCY IS IDENTIFIED.

A VACUUM TRAILER WAS DISPATCHED TO MONSANTO CHEMICAL COMPANY LOCATED AT 730 WORCESTER ROAD IN SPRINGFIELD, MA IN ORDER TO PICK UP A LOAD OF WASTE RESIN SOLUTION.  AT THE CONCLUSION OF THE LOADING PROCEDURE, THE DRIVER UTILIZED THE VACUUM ON THE TRAILER TO DRAIN THE REMAINING LIQUID IN THE TRANSFER HOSE INTO THE TRAILER.  THE TRANSFER HOSE WAS THEN SECURED IN THE HOSE TRAY LOCATED ON THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO MONSANTO'S SCALE HOUSE WHERE IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM AN OPEN DRAIN VALVE ON THE HOSE TRAY ONTO THE ASPHALT DRIVEWAY.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY AND CONTAINERIZED THE SPILL DEBRIS.  THIS MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO STORAGE PENDING FUTURE DISPOSAL TO A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, THE DRIVER HAD BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT ALL PRODUCT HAS BEEN DRAINED FROM THE TRANSFER HOSES PRIOR TO STORAGE AND THE HOSES HAVE BEEN CAPPED.  IN ADDITION, THE DRAIN VALVES ON THE HOSE TRAYS ARE TO BE INSPECTED AND IN THE CLOSED POSITION AT ALL TIMES.

column168: A CUSTOMER-OWNED CYLINDER (10# CARBON DIOXIDE) WAS PICKED UP BY ITS OWNER (WESTERN REFRIGERATION), PUT IN THE BACK OF A PICK-UP AND LEFT ON ITS SIDE WHILE CUSTOMER WAS IN RESTAURANT.  PICK UP WAS IN THE SUN, TEMPERATURE WAS ABOUT 94 DEGREES.  CYLINDER RUPTURED, CAUSED DAMAGE TO PICK-UP TAILGATE, FLOOR AND BACK WINDOW. VALVE WAS NOT LOCATED.  CUSTOMER HAD A 20 CU FT EMPTY OXYGEN CYLINDER, A SMALL FERON CYLINDER, AND A SMALL OXYGEN CYLINDER AND ACETYLENE CYLINDER INSIDE THE PICK UP.  THE CYLINER WAS IN PROPER TEST DATE, AND PROPERLY LABELLED.  CUSTOMER ARE WARNED NOT TO CARRY GASES INSIDE THEIR CLOSED VEHICLES, AND ARE PROVIDED EMERGENCY RESPONDE INFORMATION.  EVEN THOUGH THIS INCIDENT REPORT IS THE RESPONSIBILITY OF WESTERN REFRIGERATION, WE FEEL THE CUSTOMER WILL PROBABLY NOT SUBMIT A REPORT AND AS HIS SUPPLIER AND KNOWLEDGEABLE OF THE REQUIREMENTS, AND THE REPORT SHOULD BE ON RECORD.

PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM ACHER DANIELS MIDLAND, CO. LOCATED AT 554 SOUTH FRONT STREET IN ELIZABETH, NJ TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC.  LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBOR'S CONNECTICUT SERVICE CENTER LOCATED IN NEW BRITAIN, CT IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP LID OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER HERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY, PLACED THE SPILL DEBRIS IN THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION AND RESEALED THE CONTAINER.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED. IT IS BELIEVE THAT ENROUTE, THE SNAP RING CLOSURE DEVICE OPENED CAUSING THE LID TO DISLODGE.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO INSURE THAT ALL CLOSURES ARE SUFFICIENTLY SECURED.
column172: Plastic container, no capacity or description given

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE, MD TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT, INC. LOCATED AT 51 BRODERICK ROAD IN BRISTOL, CT. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT THE SECONDI TRUCK STOP IN MILFORD, CT, THE DRIVER IDENTIFIED A LEAK COMING FROM THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE BY PLACING SPEEDI DRY UNDER THE LEAK AND NOTIFIED CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC.'S 24 HOUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TELEPHONE NUMBER.  A CLEAN HARBORS EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE ALONG WITH REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE MILFORD FIRE DEPARTMENT, CONNECTICUT STATE POLICE, CONNECTICUT DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AND THE CONNECTICUT DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORATION. AT THE DIRECTION OF THE CONNECTICUT DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION, CLEAN HARBORS INITIATED PROCEDURES TO ENTER THE VAN TRAILER TO IDENTIFY THE MATERIAL BEING RELEASED.  THESE STEPS INCLUDED THE USE OF APPROPRIATE PERSONNEL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, AIR MONITORING (LEL & HNU) & A PH DETERMINATION.  THE CREW ENTERED THE VAN TRAILER, IDENTIFIED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER AND PROCEEDED TO OVERPACK THE CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  THE RESPONSE CREW ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 35 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED FROM A CRACK IN THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS.  OF THE 35 GALLONS, APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE TRAILER AND 10 GALLONS WAS RELEASED TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  ALL SPILL DEBRIS WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST USED TO SHIP THE DAMAGED CONTAINER.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.  IN ADDITION, A LOAD PREPARATION CHECKLIST IS BEING DEVELOPED THAT WILL MANDATE A STEP BY STEP PREVIEW OF EACH PHASE OF LOAD PREPARATION.  THIS CHECKLIST LABELING, MARKING & CONDITION, VEHICLE PLACARDING, AND SEGREGATION REQUIREMENT.

THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF UNDER THE HAZARDOUS DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

THE WET BOX WAS DISCOVERED ON PD8 147 DR. AT 01:36 BY THE LOADER, DAN ROUSSEAU.  DAN NOTIFIED THE AREA SUPERVISOR, MIKE SPURRI IN TURN CALLED THE PSC. AFTER CONSULTING THE DECISION TREE AND GUIDEBOOK I CONTAINED THE WET BOX IN THE SPILL TUB, AND RETURNED TO THE PSC WITH THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THE DMP WAS STARTED AT 01:45 AND OCMPLETED AT 02:15. THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF UNDER THE HAZARDOUS DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.  THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN REPACKED AND SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.

GOT A CALL FROM WILMINGTON AT 18:30 CENTER CAGE, ABOUT WET PACKAGE WITH A CORROSIVE LABEL ON IT WAS TOLD IT WAS NOT LEAKING OUT OF BOX AND IT WAS NOT IN SPILL TUB.  USING THE DECISION TREE GOGGLES, GLOVES AND APRON I WENT TO GET IT AND BRING BACK TO DMP AREA.  I LOOK IT UP IN EMERGENCY GUIDE BOOK AND SHEET AND THEN I OPENED BOX TO FIND 1 2.5 GALLON PLASTIC WITH LOOSE CAP.  HAD LEAKED 1-1 1/2 PINT FROM IT AND STAY CONTAIN IN TO BOX. PUT ALL WET CARDBOARD, SPEEDI DRY AND SODIUM BICARBONATE TO DMP BAG AND PUT THROUGH THE DMP PROCEDURES.  FINISH 19:15.

AT 04:10, PAUL LAVIOE RESPOND TO MARLBORO BOXLINE FOR A WET PACKAGE. GLOVES, APRON, GOGGLES.  THIS WAS NO SPILL WET CARDBOARD ONLY.  HE CONTAINERIZED PACKAGE IN SPILL BIN AND BROUGHT TO DMP AREA.  AT DMP AREA I TOOL CONTROL OF PACKAGE, CHECKING LABELS I FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO HAVE 5 PART FORM AND DIAMOND LABEL FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  FOLLOWING DECISION TREE, AND GUIDELINES FOR UN1193 I OPENED PACKAGE DISCOVERED LOOSE CAP WITH A MINIMUM LOSS OF FLUID.  I TAPED CAPS REBOXED AND SENT ON TO CONSIGNEE. I FINISHED ALL PAPER WORK AND PROCEDURES AT 10:25 HOURS.  THE PACKAGE SHOULD HAVE ARROWS FOR THIS SIDE UP, TO HELP PRELOADERS TO KEEP CAPS UPS SO NO EXTRA PRESSURE IS ADDED TO CAP WHICH CAN CAUSE THESE KIND TO LEAK.

CONTENTS WERE FOUND ALL OVER FLOOR ON PD-6. I NEUTRALIZED IT WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE AND ABSORBED WITH DRY ALL.  CONTENTS AND BOX WERE MALLINCKRODTED, ACCORDING TO PROCEDURES, (APRON, GOGGLES, GLOVES, AND BOOTS WERE WORN). PAPERWORK COMPLETED AND FAXED.  ENTIRE CONTENTS WERE MALLINCKRODTED.

column168: DRIVER JOHN WILLIAMS WAS SORTING THROUGH PACKAGES ON HIS PACKAGE CAR WHEN HE FELT A BOX WAS WET. HE ALSO NOTICED AN ODOR EMITTING FROM THE PACKAGE. JOHN LEFT THE IMMEDIATE AREA AND CALLED ME AT THE CENTER FOR NOTIFICATION. I USED THE DECISION TREE TO EVALUATE THE CORRECT RESPONSE WHICH WAS TO CALL THE CROSSVILLE FIRE DEPT. THEY ARE THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS FOR ANY INCIDENTS IN THIS AREA. WHILE USING PPE TO ASSESS THE SPILL, THEY ALSO CALLED SHIPPER & COMPANY THAT MANUFACTURED MATERIAL. APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT LEAKED THROUGH THE CARTON WITH THE FIRE DEPT. CLEANING UP THE SPILL ON SITE. ALSO CONSIGNEE CAME TO THE FIRE DEPT. TO PICKUP THEIR PACKAGE. IT CONTAINED 2 QTS OF 10% HYDROCHLORIC ACID. TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS ALL EMPLOYEE'S WILL BE REVIEWED AT PCM- ON PROPER HAZ MAT HANDLING PROCEDURES PLACEMENT OF THESE PACKAGES, HANDLING, AND RESPONSE. IF DAMAGED PACKAGE IS FOUND THEY SHOULD ,1. NOT TOUCH 2.LEAVE THE IMMEDIATE AREA 3. AND NOTIFY A SUPERVISOR.

column168: WHEN OFFLOADING FREIGHTER NW903 OF APRIL 27, 1994, OUR EQUIPMENT SERVICE EMPLOYEE DISCOVERED THREE PLASTIC DRUMS THAT WERE LEAKING. THE EMPLOYEE REMOVED THE THREE DRUMS AND CLEANUP ALL THAT HAD SPILL ONTO THE PALLET. AS SOON AS WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL I CALED THE 1-800-NUMBER ON SHIPPER DECLARATION.. HOWEVER, THE PERSON ON THE OTHER END COULD NOT GIVE ME ANY ASSISTANCE. FOR ONE HE HAD NO INFORMATION ON THE SHIPPER OR FORWARDER... SECOND THIS SUBSTANCE WAS NOT IN HIS COMPANY.. FINALLY, HE WAS ABLE TO GET SOME INFORMATION ON THE MANUFACTOR. THEY GAVE ME A LOCAL NUMBER FOR THE MANUFACTOR OF THIS SUBSTANCE BUT THEY WERE NOT FAMILAR WITH THIS PRODUCT. MEANWHILE I CHECKED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDANCE FOR AIRCRAFT INCIDENT INVOLVING DANGEROUS GOOD BOOK. I READ WHAT I SHOULD DO FOR CLASS "9" INCIDENT AND DISCOVER THAT THERE WAS NO DANGER TO THE CREW OR PLANE.. AT WHICH TIME I REASSURED THE CREW THAT IT WAS SAFE TO TAKE PLANE. I CONTINUE TO WAIT FOR SOMEONE TO ADVISE ME WHAT THE ACTUAL SUBSTANCE THAT HAS SPILL ON THE PLANE. THERE WERE TWO EMPLOYEE WHO COME IN PHYSICAL CONTACT WITH THE SUBSTANCE..I NEEDED TO KNOW IF THERE WAS ANY HEALTH HAZARDOUS TO MY EMPLOYEE. FINALLY I GOT HOLD OF THE TULSA FACTORY, WHERE THE SUBSTANCE IS PRODUCE..THEY FAX A COPY OF THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET. IT QUITE RIDICIOUS THAT A SHIPPER PUT DOWN A 1-800-NUMBER THAT WAS NO INFORM.

column168: PACKAGE DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING OFFLOAD SORT.  PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED FOR DANGEROUS GOODS; THERE WAS NO SHIPPERS DECLARATION. INSPECTION REVEALED A 4L CAN WITH FRICTION LID, ENCLOSED IN A PLASTIC BAG, INSIDE A PLAIN CARDBOARD BOX.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR MSDS, BUT DID NOT HAVE MSDS, NOR DID SHIPPER UNDERSTAND WHAT MSDS WAS FOR.  WE CONTACTED MFGR TO OBTAIN MSDS, WHICH INDICATES FLASH POINT OF 104 F.  LOCAL FAA/CAFSO WAS NOTIDIED.  PACKAGE HELD AT STATION PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

HOWEVER, DUE TO THE PACKAGEING MATERIAL SIGMA IS KNOWN FOR, IT WAS A UN SPECIFICATION PACKAGE PACKED APPROPRIATELY.  IT SIMPLY WAS DAMAGED BY OTHER THE DROP.  THE PACKAGE SORTERS WERE CAUTIONED ABOUT ENSURING PACKAGES ARE PLACED SECURELY ON THE CONVEYOR BELT.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND THE PACAKGE RETURNED TO THEM ONCE PLACED WITHIN A SALVAGE DRUM PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: EMPLOYEE WAS TRAVELING EAST ON A GRAVEL ROAD 3 MILES NORTH OF DUNNELL APPROX 25-30 MPH AT APPROX 2 PM.  THE ROAD HAD BEEN GRADED AND THERE WAS GRAVEL PILED ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE ROAD.  WE BELIEVE THE TANK RODE HIGH ENOUGH ON THAT PIPE OF GRAVE THAT CAUSED IT TO OVERTURN.  IT STAYED IN THE ROAD AND CONNECTED TO THE PICKUP, BUT HAD SHEARED OFF THE ROLL CAGE AND THE FRONT VALVE.  A WITNESS TO THE OVERTURN PICKED UP THE EMPLOYEE AND ALL THE PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE CALLED AND THE FIRE DEPT ARRIVED AT THE SCENE UNTIL DANGER WAS PAST.

EAGLE TRANSPORT DELIVERED A LOAD OF DIESEL FUEL TO THIS FACILITY ON MAY 31, 1994.  I HAVE A 10,000 GALLON ABOVE GROUND DOUBLE CONICAL DIESEL FUEL HOLDING TANK.  I READ THE SIDE GLASS FLOAT DEVICE AND THOUGHT IT READ 27 INCHES.  WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED WITH THE FUEL, MY SHOP MECHANIC STUCK THE TANK PHYSICALLY AND IT READ 29 INCHES.  HE TOLD THE DRIVER TO UNLOAD WHICH CAUSED TO THE OVERFLOW OF 20 TO 25 GALLONS.  ALL WAS CONTAINED EXCEPT ABOUT 10 GALLONS WHICH WENT ON THE GROUND.  THE SPILL DID NOT REACH ANY WATER OR SEWER SYSTEMS.  I NOTIFIED ENVIRONMENTAL CLAIM SERVICE LINDSEY MORDEN WHO THEN NOTIFIED AGUSTA INDUSTRIAL SERVICES FOR THE CLEAN UP AND DISPOSAL.  I ALSO NOTIFIED THE GEORGIA EPD THE CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED JUNE 6,1994 AND NOW ARE WAITING ON THE ANALYTICAL FOR PROPER DISPOSAL OF THE FIRT.  OUR OVERFLOW SAFETY ALARM FAILED TO OPERATE DUE TO IT BEING SHORTED OUT.  WE HAVE GONE TO A BELL ALARM SYSTEM THAT WILL ACTIVATE AND CLOSE A CHECK VALVE AUTOMATICALLY WHEN THE TANK IS 90 PERCENT FULL.  HOPEFULLY THIS WILL ELIMINATE THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.

column168: CAP SEALED AND OR BOTTLE SEAMS LEAKED ACID WHICH CAUSED CARTON DETERIOATION THUS COLLAPSING PALLET TO MULTIPLY DAMAGE.

CONRAIL UNLOAD W. J ERTEL AT 1020 HOURS ON MAY 9TH NOTICED FUEL OIL "ESACPING" FROM THE A-END ACTIVATOR BOX ON GATX 57025.  A GATX MOBILE UNIT RESPONDED AND REPLACED THE GASKET BETWEEN THE EDUCATION PIPE FLANGE AND THE STUDDING RING.  THIS SAME CAR HAD BEEN INSPECTED BY GATX ON MAY 6TH FOR A SUSPECTED PROBLEM WITH THE SAME VALVE; AT THAT TIME THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED.  THIS REPORT IS LATE BECAUSE OF LOST PAPER WORK BETWEEN SELKIRK AND PHILADELPHIA.

AT 1000 HOURS ON MAY 21ST THE BEACON PARK YARDMASTER WAS WALKING PAST THE FLEXI FLO STORAGE TRACK AND NOTICED A 5 GALLON BUCKET TIED UNDER ACFX 75118.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET WAS SLOWLY DRIPPING.  CLEAN HARBORS CHECKED THE SOIL FOR CONTAMINATION AND FOUND NONE.  ASHLAND CHEMICAL RESPONDED AND TIGHTENED THE BOTTOM VALVE.

A VACUUM TRAILER WAS DISPATCHED TO HOWMET TURBINE COMPONENTS LOCATED AT 1 HOWMET DRIVE IN HAMPTON, VA IN ORDER TO PICK UP A LOAD OF HAZARDOUS WASTE LIQUID, N.O.S. (CONTAINING CHROMIUM).  AT THE CONCLUSION OF THE LOADING PROCEDURE, THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE INITIATED STEPS TO DRAIN THE HOSES PRIOR TO SECURING THEM FOR TRANSPORTATION.  THE DRIVER WAS DRAINING THE LIQUID REMAINING IN THE HOSE SLIPPED FROM THE DRIVERS HAND AND OVERTURNED THE PAIL RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 1-1.5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL ONTO AN ASPHALT PARKING AREA.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND ABSORBED THE FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY.  ALL SPILL DEBRIS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THIS LOAD WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGHT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILIEY LISTED ON THE HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS SITUATION, THE DRIVER OF THIS VEHICLE HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT ALL EQUIPMENT USED TO DRAIM A VEHICLE'S TRANSFER HOSES IS SECURED IN ORDER TO PREVENT THE CONTAINER FROM TIPPING OVER WHILE THE HOSES ARE BEING DRAINED.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM SOUTHERN MAINE INDUSTRIES LOCATED 45 HUTCHINSON DRIVE IN GORHAM, ME TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT, INC.  LOCATED AT 51 BRODERICK ROAD ON BRISTOL, CT.  DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBOR'S SOUTH PORTLAND SERVICE CENTER, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF LIQUID HAD ESCAPED FROM THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY AND RECONTAINERIZED THE CONTENTS OF THE CONTAINER.  IT IS BELIEVE THAT A SHARP OBJECT IN THE CONTAINER PUNCTURED THE INNER ALLOWING RESIDUAL LIQUID THAT WAS NOT VISIBLE AT THE TIME OF LOADING TO ESCAPE THROUGHT THE FIBER BOX.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER LOCATION, ALL CONTAINER WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, ALL DRIVER AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.  IN ADDITION, THE SHIPPER HAD BEEN INSTRUCTED TO USE AN ALTERNATE CONTAINER FOR ANY MATERIAL THAT WOULD POTENTIALLY CONTAIN RESIDUAL LIQUID.

column42: PROPIONIC ACID WITH NOT LESS THAN 10% AND LESS THAN 90% ACID BY MASS
column168: ON MAY 18, 1994, AIR CARGO RECEIVED A SHIPMENT FROM OPERATIONS THAT WAS LEAKING SOME TYPE OF LIQUID.  LCSA PAUL PLAZA DETERMINED THAT THE SUBSTANCE WAS PROPIONIS ACID, A CORROSIVE THAT IS REGULATED BY THE I.A.T.A. FIELD OFFICE AND NOTIFIED SPECIAL AGENT MICHELLE JEKEL. SHE SAID SHE WOULD COME OUT AND INVESTIGATE.  AT 0940, F.A.A. AGENTS M. JEKEL AND L. SHELTON PHOTOGRAPHED AND DOCUMENTED IRREGULARITIES WITH THE SHIPMENT THAT WAS IDENTIFIED AT THIS POINT AS AN UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT.  AFTER THEIR INVESTIGATION THEY INFORMED CSS DENIS SCHUMACHER TO HOLD THE SHIPMENT AT THE DELTA CARGO FACILITY UNTIL INSTRUCTED OTHERWISE BY THEIR OFFICE.  DELTA WAS GIVEN INSTRUCTIONS BY THE F.A.A. TO RELEASE THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE AT APPROXIMATELY 1300.  AT THIS POINT U.P.S. WAS ADVISED OF THE PROBLEM AND TOLD THEY COULD PICK UP THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PICKED UP BY U.P.S. AT 1530.

column168: OP CTR REPORTED LTC IN HAMLET, NC CAUSE LEAKING FROM TOP.  I CONTACTED SHIPPER THROUGH CHEMTREC.  SHIPPER RESPONDED AND REPLACED RUPTURE DISC CAR SENT ONTO DESTINATION.

column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: CSXT TRAIN R530-21 STRUCK A TRACTOR TRAILER TRUCK ON A PRIVATE CROSSING SOUTH OF BELLS.  TR MP-F-308.31 LOCOMOTIVES AND 35 CARS DERAILED.  TRUCK DRIVER D.O.S. ONE TANK CAR OF PHENOL AND 2 TANK CARS OF PARAFFIN WERE RUPTRED AND SPILLED ENTIRE CONTENTS ON TO GROUND AND WITH A WET WEATHER CANAL.  CSXT RESPONDED, CLEANUP CONTRACTOR.  FERGUSON HARBOR FROM MEMPHIS, TN.  CSXT HAZ MAT RESPONDED TO MANAGER CLEAN UP.  CANAL WAS DAMED UP DOWNSTREAM TO CONTAIN CONTAMINATION.  400,000 GALLONS OF WATER AND 5,000 TARS OF SOIL CONTAMINATED WITH PHENOL HAVE BEEN REMOVED AND STOCK PILED ON SITE.  OTHER CONTAMINATED LADING ALSO STOCK PILED FOR DISPOSAL.  SITE CLEANUP IS ON GOING.

WHILE THE DRIVER WAS PUMPING OF A LOAD OF #2 DIESEL FUEL INTO CUSTOMER STORAGE USING A ROPER PUMP WITH A CROSS OVERLINE THAT ALLOWS THE INDIVIDUAL TO PUMP OFF EITHER SIDE OF A TRACTOR, THE CAP ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE PUMP LINE OF THE PUMP BLEW OFF THE CONNECTION.  THE PUMP WAS SHUT DOWN AND THE SPILL WAS CLEANED BY BOTH SEABOARD TANK LINES, INC. PERSONNEL AND OUR CELAN UP CONTRACTOR.  THE DEBRIS WAS DISPOSED OF.  THE PENNSYLVANIA DER WAS NOTIFIED.
TRAINMASTER REPORTED CREW SMELLED SOMETHING AROUND CAR.  DSH INSPECTED CAR AND FOUND LIQUID WAS LOOSE.  DJH TIGHTENED VALVE AND SECURED CAR.  CAR SENT TO DESTINATION.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: VEHICLE WAS INVOLVED IN A TRAFFIC ACCIDENT WHICH CAUSED THE VEHICLE TO OVERTURN.  LEFT SIDE OF VEHICLE WAS PUNCTURED UPON CONTACT WITH GUARD RAIL AND HIGHWAY SURFACE.  RESIN SOLUTION LEAKED ONTO HIGHWAY OVERPASS, AND ENTERED STORM DRAINS WHICH CONVEYED SOME RESIN TO EDGE OF RAILROAD TRACKS BENEATH HIGHWAY OVERPASS.  APPROXIMATELY 4,600 GALLONS OF 6,000 GALLON LOAD WAS PUMPED VIA VACUUM TRUCK ONTO EMPTY CARGO TANK AND TRANSPORTED TO MANUFACTURING PLANT IN NEWARK, NJ.  ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS SOLIDIFIED WITH ABSORBANT MEDIA AND TRANSPORTED TO AN AUTHORIZED WASTE DISPOSAL FACILITY (LAIDLAW IN PINEWOOD, SC).  THE VEHICLE WAS TOWED TO SULLIVAN'S SALVAGE YARD IN BALTIMORE.  SEVERAL PERSONS AT SCENE OF ACCIDENT WERE TAKEN TO LOCAL AREA HOSPITAL AND RELEASED WITHOUT TREATMENT.
BOX WAS FOUND IN TRAILER BLOCKED AND BRACED, BUT WET.  UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE BOTTLE WAS CRACKED AND DAMAGED.  LOST MATERIAL EVAPORATED.

column168: PRODUCT WAS BEING OFFLOADED BY GRAVITY. ALL INDICATORS (SIGHT GLASS AND SLACK HOSE) SHOWED PRODUCT OFFLOAD COMPLETE. AT APPROXIMATELY 9:05 HOURS, SATURDAY, MAY 28, 1994, THE BRAKEMAN OF YPSP-13 REPORTED THAT HE ALLEGEDLEY SMELLED PRODUCT ODOR COMING FROM AT SOUTH PHILADELPHIA YARD.  CAR WAS SHIPPED FROM LYONDELL CHEMICAL IN HOUSTON, TX ON/ABOUT 5/13/94 ENROUTE TO AN ASHLAND CHEMICAL FACILITY LOCATED ABOUT ONE HALF MILE FROM THE S. PHILADELPHIA YARD.  A MECHANICAL SUPERVISOR FROM ASHLAND CHEMICAL RESPONDED TO THE CAR AND COULD ONLY SPECULATE THAT PRODUCT ODOR WAS COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET BALL ADAPTER FLANGE.  NO VAPOR OR PRODUCT LEAK COULD BE DETECTED.  ONLY MINIMAL PRODUCT ODOR COULD BE DETECTED AFTER WIPING THE AREA AROUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET. THE CAR WAS DELIVERED TO ASHLAND CHEMICAL FOR THEIR FURTHER HANDLING AND CORRECTIVE ACTION.
PACKAGE WAS FOUND ON THE UNLOAD DOOR 22.  IT WAS CRUSHED WITH ONE PINT CAN LEAKING.  ALL PROCEDURES WERE FOUND TO HANDLE AND CONTAIN LEAKING PACKAGE.
PACKAGE FOUND DOOR 62.  THERE WAS LEAKING FROM A LOOSE CAP.  THE PACK CONDITION WAS INSUFFICIENT.  ALL PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN THE SPILL.

RECEIVED A CALL AT 12:30 FRM BILL SINTIRIS ABOUT A LEAKING CORROSIVE MATERIALS PACKAGE AT 29DR.  HE STATED IT WAS HYDROCHLORIC ACID UN1789 CLASS AND THAT IT WAS IN THE REAR OF THE FEEDER.  AFTER RECEIVING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE GUIDE I RESPONDED TO 29 DOOR WEARING GOGGLES, GLOVES AND APRON.  I PLACED THE LEAKER INTO A SPILL TUB INTO A SPILL TUB WITH SPEEDY DRY.  THERE WAS NO SPILLAGE ON THE FLOOR SO I RETURNED TO PSC AT 13:28 WITH THE CONTAINED SPILL.  THE BOX CONTAINED 4 QUARTS OF COMPOUND CLEANING LIQUID ONE OF WHICH HAD A LOOSE CAP.  PROCESSED THE WET BOX UNDER THE DMP AND HAZ MAT PROCESS.  CLEAN UP COMPLETED AT 13:55.
BOX FOUND LOADED IN PACKAGE CAR LEAKING, DAMAGED IN LOAD PROCESS, DENTED, CAUSED TOP OF ONE CAN TO POP OFF.
PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED ON SORT AISLE.  IT HAD BEEN TURNED OVER.  AFTER EXAMINING THE PACKAGE, WE NOTICED IT HAD LOOSE CAPS.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED ON WEST DOCK.  THE PACKAGE HAD BEEN DROPPED; AS A RESULT, THE CAP WAS CRACKED AND 1 GALLON LEAKED ONTO THE FLOOR.  THE PACKAGE WAS PROPERLY HANDLED AND CLEANED BY QUALIFIED RESPONDERS.
THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED WHILE UNLOADING A BULK VAN.  QUALIFIED RESPONDERS IDENTIFIED THE PACKAGE.  IT HAD FALLEN FROM A TOP SHELF AND HAD CRACKED THE CAP.
THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED ON GREEN BELT.  A LOOSE CAP ALLOWED CONTENTS TO LEAK ON OTHER PACKAGES.  IT WAS PROPERLY CLEANED BY QUALIFIED RESPONDERES.
RESPONDED TO WET PACKAGE AT SOUTH CENTER.  DETERMINED BUCKET WAS CRACKED. REPLACED BUCKET AND SENT AFFECTED WASTE TO MALLINKRODT.

column168: PURITAN-BENNETT DRIVER WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON INTERSTATE 4 ABOUT 3 MILES EAST OF TAMPA, FL ON MAY 31, 1994 ENROUTE TO MAKE A DELIVERY TO A CUSTOMER IN TAMPA, FLORIDA.  HE WAS DRIVING A COE FREIGHTLINER TRACTOR AND PULLING A TANK TRAILER LOADED WITH LIQUID NITROUS. OXIDE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0130, HIS TRACTOR WAS STRUCK ON THE LEFT-FRONT DRIVE TIRE BY A 1988 CHEVROLET THAT WAS PASSING HIM ON THE LEFT.  THE DRIVER SPECULATES THAT THE OTHER DRIVER FELL ASLEEP AT THE WHEEL.  SHE WAS TICKETED FOR CARELESS DRIVING BY POLICE.  OUR DRIVER SWERVED TO AVOID A DIRECT IMPACT WITH THE CHEVROLET AND WENT OFF THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD INTO A DITCH. SHIFTING OF THE LOAD CAUSED THE TRAILER TO LEAN TO THE RIGHT AND IT WAS DECIDED TO TRANSFER THE LOAD OF THE TRAILER TO A SECOND TRAILER TO AVOID ANY POSSIBLE CHANGE OF OVERTURNING THE TRAILER WHILE TRYING TO DRIVE OUT OF THE DITCH.  AFTER TRANSFER OF THE LOAD, THE TRAILER WAS PULLED OUT OF THE DITCH BY THE TRACTOR WITHOUT INCIDENT.  THE HIGHWAY PATROL CLOSED THE HIGHWAY & REROUTED TRAFFIC IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE ACCIDENT AS A PRECAUTION BUT OPENED IT BACK UP UNTIL THE SECOND TRAILER ARRIVED TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT.  AT NO TIME WAS THERE A LEAK OR SPILL OF PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER.

column168: TANK CAR FOUND TO BE LEAKING DURING INBOUND INSPECTION. ATSF RESPONDERS DETERMINED SOURCE OF RELEASE TO BE A DEFECTIVE GASKET BETWEEN THE TANK CAR TAND AND BOTTOM OUTLET PIPE. THREE OF FOUR SEGMENTS OF THE GASKET WERE DEFORMED BETWEEN OUTLET SECUREMENT BOLTS. ALL BOLTS WERE TIGHT. CAR WAS TRANSLOADED INTO ANOTHER TANK CAR AND FORWARDED TO DESINATION. RELEASED PRODUCT EVAPORATED BEFORE COLLECTING ON GROUND UNDER CAR.

TANK CAR FOUND TO BE RELEASING VAPOR FROM PROTECTIVE HOUSING AREA WHILE IN YARD.  ATSF RESPONDERS DETERMINED CAUSE TO BE A RELEASE OF PRODUCT AT A FITTING IN THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  AAR PUEBLO PERSONNEL MADE FIRST ENTRY AND FOUND LEAKING SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  ALL ATTEMPTS TO SEAT THE VALVE FAILED.  CAR WAS OFF LOADED TO TRUCKS, THEN RELOADED INTO ANOTHER RAIL CAR.  PRODUCT WAS REDUCED TO ^0 PSI, BUT WITH INCREASED AMBIENT TEMPERATURE, VAPOR RELEASE RESUMED.  ATSF PERSONNEL REMOVED AND REPLACED SAFETY RELIEF VALVE, THEN SENT CAR TO HOME SHOP.  INJURY WAS TO AN EMPLOYEE ALLEGING INHALATION OF VAPOR AFTER CAR WAS EMPTIED.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER ONE 30 POUND CONTAINER WAS FOUND DAMAGED APPARENTLY BY A FORKLIFT BLADE.  AN ESTIMATED 20 LBS WAS RELEASED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  AN ABSORBENT WAS PLACED ON THE SPILL TO MINIMIZE ANY DUST PROBLEM AND THE TRAILER WAS PLACED ON THE YARD.  THRU A MIXUP THE TRAILER WAS SENT TO A LOCAL TRUCK WASH TO BE CLEANED.  WHEN THE WATER FROM THE HIGH PRESSURE WASHER HIT THE MATERIAL A LARGE DUST CLOUD FORMED COATING THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER AND THE WASH BAY.  TWO EMPLOYEES IN THE WASH BAY EXPERIENCED DIFFICULTY IN BREATHING DUE TO THE HIGH DUST CONCENTRATION AND WERE SENT TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL TO BE CHECKED OUT.  THEY WERE TREATED AND RELEASED WITH NO EFFECTS FOR THE EXPOSURE NOTED.  ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICES, INC. WAS CONTRACTED TO PREFORM THE CLEANUP OPERATION WHEICH CONSISTED OF DECONTAMINATING THE TRAILER, WASHING DOWN THE WASH BAY AND CLEANING OUT THE SEWER SYSTEM.  ALL WORK WAS COMPLETED TO THE SATISFACTION OF THE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL RESOURCES AND THE LOCAL SEWER AUTHORITIES.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: ON 5/3/94, AT APPROXIMATELY 0610 HRS. I, KAREN NOCHOLS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR, INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177, INVESTIGATED A LEAKING SHIPMENT INSIDE DOOR C-17 OF OUR SORT FACILITY AT THE SAME ADDRESS. THE SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED BY JACK BUCCI/SORT AREA MANAGER. THE SHIPMENT WAS PACKAGED. IN A FIBERBOARD BOX WHICH HAD NO MARKINGS OR LABELS AFFIXED WHICH INDICATED THE PACKAGE TO CONTAIN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPERS CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ACCOMPANYING THE SHIPMENT. INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX I FOUND 2 X 5 GALLON METAL DRUMS WITH FRICTION TYPE CLOSURES AND NO OTHER MEANS TO SECURE CLOSURE. THESE 5 GALLON METAL DRUMS CONTAINED VULKEM 640 ALUMINUM BRUSHABLE SEALANT/ONE PART POLYURETHANE. A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET HAS BEEN OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER INDICATING A FLASHPOINT O 103 DEGREES F. NONE OF THIS MATERIAL LEAKED AND NEITHER METAL DRUM WAS DAMAGED. ALSO, INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS 1 X 1 GALLON METAL CAN WITH A FRICTION TYPE CLOSURE AND NO OTHER MEANS TO SECURE CLOSURE. THERE WAS NO INDICATION ON THE METAL CAN WHAT THE CONTENTS WERE, HOWEVER, THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET PROVIDED BY THE SHIPPER INDICATED THE PRODUCT IS VULKEM 171 PRIMER POLYURETHANE PRIMER WITH A FLASHPOINT OF 105 DEGREES F. THIS METAL CAN WAS DENTED IN THE SIDE POSSIBLY FORCING FRICTION CLOSURE OFF. APPROXIMATELY 0.5 GALLONS LEAKED. SHREDDED PAPER WAS POSSIBLY USED AS SHOCK ABSORBENT MATERIAL, BUT NO OTHER ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE USED. THE SHIPMENT IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD IN OUR HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING RELEASE BY THE FAA.

ON THURSDAY, 5/5/94, AT ABOUT 0105 HOURS, UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORATION SAFETY, T.M. ROBINSON WAS CALLED AT HIS RESIDENCE BY UPRR SUPERVISOR YARD OPERATIONS/ADDIS, LA.  THAT THIS TANK CAR WAS REPORTED, BY YARD PERSONNEL, TO BE SPEWING FROM THE TOP.  SUPERVISOR E. TROSCLAIRE FURTHER ADVISED THAT THE CAR WOULD BE ISOLATED UNTIL THE LEAK WAS CORRECTED.  UPON ARRIVAL ROBINSON REMOVED SEAL "TRIAD CHEMICALS #52994" FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING SECUREMENT PIN AND OPENED SAME.  THIS INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE LEAKAGE WAS FROM THE SAMPLE LINE VALVE. ROBINSON WAS ABLE TO TURN THE NEEDLE VALVE ONE HALF TURN AND THIS SECURED THE CAR FROM LEAKING.  IN ADDITION, IT WAS NOTED THAT THE PLUG IN THE SAMPLE LINE VALVE WAS ITSELF AN AUXILLARY VALVE WHICH ALSO WAS OPEN ABOUT ONE AND ONE HALF TURNS.  THIS WAS CLOSED ALSO BY ROBINSON.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AT ABOUT 0215 HOURS.  IN ADDITION TO THE CHEMTREC NOTIFICATION, ROBINSON TELEPHONED MR. BOB MCKEE, SHIPPING SUPERVISOR FOR TRIAD CHEMICALS AT DONALDSONVILLE, LA.  MCKEE WAS INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT BY ROBINSON.

S/A BALLANCE RECEIVED INFORMATION FROM BONNIE OF UPMF THAT CONTAINER APLU-454052 WAS FOUND LEAKING.  THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN PLACED THE NIGHT BEFORE IN THE SUGAR DOCK AREA.  UPON ARRIVAL S/A, BALLANCE OPENED THE CONTAINER AND WAS UNABLE TO LOCATE THE LEAKING SUBSTANCE.  THE CONTAINER WAS REMOVED FROM THE CHASSE AND PLACED ON A ROLL OF PLASTIC.  MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED TO ASSIST IN REMOVING OF FREIGHT TO ACCESS THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  IT WAS DETERMINED TWO PRODUCTS WERE LEAKING.  ONE WAS A NONREGULATED LUBERCATING OIL, THE SECOND WAS LISTED AS A CORROSIVE LIQUID NOS CONTAINING FATTY QUATERNARY.  THE CORROSIVE LIQUID DRUM WAS DAMAGED BY A PALLET WHICH WAS FORCED AGAINST IT BY A FORKLIFT.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH DAVE HOHENFELDT OF APL.  HE ADVISED INFORMATION WAS RECEIVED FROM THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER THAT SEVERAL OTHER HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES WERE PRESENT ON THE CONTAINER WHICH WERE NOT LISTED ON THE SHIPPING PAPERS.  THE LEAKING MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND OVER PACKED.  WASTE WAS DISPOSED OF IN A 55 GALLON DRUM.

column168: ON 050594 AT APPROXIMATELY 7PM REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM MTO LAWLER THAT A SWITCHMAN HAD BEEN SPLASHED BY ASPHALT LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THIS CAR. REEDER ARRIVED AND DISCOVERED THAT THE FLANGE COVERING THE LIQUID LINE WAS NOT BOLTED DOWN.  OF THE FOUR STUDS, ONE WAS MISSING ENTIRELY.  ONE NUT WAS MISSING ENTIRELY, ONE WAS LYING ON THE FLANGE IN A POOL OF ASPHALT, THE FOURTH WAS STUCK ON THE STUD, BUT NOT ACTUALLY STARTED ON THE THREADS. REEDER OBTAINED THREE NEW NUTS AND REPLACED THEM ON THE FLANGE.  THE SWITCHMAN WAS NOT INJURED, ONLY HIS CLOTHES WERE SOILED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

THIS PACKAGE OF PYRIDINE WAS RECEIVED BY INTERLINE FREIGHT FROM FOREWAY EXPRESS INC. AND WAS ON PUTNAM TRAILER #973 PARKED AT PUTNAM TRANSFER'S DOCK BEING UNLOADED BY PUTNAM EMPLOYEE MARVIN CINQUEPALMI. THE TRAILER WAS MOSTLY UNLOADED WHEN THE PACKAGE WAS SET DOWN TOO HARD. THE SUPERVISOR ON DUTY AT THE TIME WAS TOM ARNOLD. THE PACKAGE CONTAINED TWO (GALLON JARS), ONE WAS BROKED THAT ALLOWED THE CONTENTS TO SPILL OUT INTO THE TRAILER. MARVIN STATED HE DID NOT REALIZE IT WAS SET DOWN TOO HARD UNTIL IT STARTED LEAKING. ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PLACED OVER THE SPILLED CONTENTS AND THE TRAILER WAS PARKED OUT IN THE YARD WITH THE DOORS OPEN TO AIR OUT. PICTURES WERE TAKEN OF THE PACKAGE SHOWING THE CONDITION AND CONTENTS AND ARE ON FILE IN PICTURE POUCH #94-17, DATED 5-4-94. B&B UNDERGROUND, P.O. BOX 2541, LANDCASTER, OHIO 43130, PHONE 614-681-9902, WAS CALLED TO DISPOSE OF THE SPILLED CONTENTS. THEY SENT TWO MEN, ONE BARNEY COOK IN CHARGE. THEY PUT THE DAMAGED PACKAGE IN A RECOVERY DRUM ALONG WITH CONTENTS SWEEP OUT OF THE TRAILER. THE TRAILER WAS WASHED OUT AND THE USED WATER ALSO WAS PUT IN THE RECOVERY DRUM, SEALED TO BE DISPOSED OF BY B&B UNDER GROUND AT A PROPER LOCATION. B&B UNDERGROUND CHARGE FOR RESPONSE IS $400.00.

column168: I RECEIVED A CALL AT PSC AT 01:10 FROM JOHN BARBER IN THE SECONDARY ABOUT A PACKAGE EMITTING A STRONG SMELL IN THE SECONDARY SLIDE. HE TOLD ME IT WAS A 5 PART HAZARDOUS. I RESPONDED WEARING GLOVES, GOGGLES AND AN APRON AND AFTER CONSULTING THE DECISION TREE AND THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE I PLACED THE PACKAGE IN A SPILL TUB. I BROUGHT THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE BOX. THE PACKAGE CONTAINED AMMONIUM HYDROXIDE SO IN ACCORDANCE WITH OUR STANDARD PROCEDURE AND THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE, SUE WERTZ AND I DONNED THE SCBAS AND REMOVED THE PACKAGE TO THE OUTSIDE TO REPACKAGE IT. WE PROCESSED THE DAMAGED BOX UNDER THE DAMAGED MATERIALS PROGRAM FOR PROPER DISPOSAL CLASSIFICATION. I TIGHTENED THE CAPS AND REPACKED THE CONTENTS FOR SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. CLEAN UP BEGAN AT 01:25 AND WAS COMPLETED AT 02:20.

AT 01:15 DMP AREA RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM THE SECONDARY. CHERYL COLLINS RESPONDED TO THE CALL AFTER SHE CONSULTED THE DECISION TREE AND THE DAMAGE RESPONSE BOOK. SHE PROCEEDED TO THE SECONDARY WITH APRON, GOGGLES, GLOVES, TWO SPILL TUBS AND SPEEDI DRY. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED INSIDE THE BOX SHE CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE IN A SPILL TUB WITH SPEEDI DRY. SHE BROUGHT THE SPILL TUB WITH THE LEAKER DOWN TO THE DMP AREA. WHERE I BEGAN TO PROCESS THE CARDBOARD AND THE CONTAMINATED SPEEDI DRY UNDER THE DAMAGED MATERIALS PROGRAM AT 03:00. A DAMAGE WAS WRITTEN. THE PACKAGE ITSELF CONTAINED A FIVE GALLON INSIDE A BOX. NO CUSHIONING OR PARTITIONS WERE USED CAUSING THE PAIL TO MOVE FREELY IN THE BOX. REST OF THE SHIPMENT WAS SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. DONE 03:23.

ON 05-04-94 AT 0350 HAZ MAT AREA MANAGER JIM CURTIS REPORTED A SPILL IN THE HAZ MAT FEED AREA OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. HAZ MAT COORDINATOR FRAN VANCE AND P/T HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICIAN JON MOOTS RESPONDED TO THE SPILL. UPON ARRIVAL WE FOUND A BROWN FIBREBOARD BOX LEAKING ON ODOROUS LIQUID. THE BOX WAS MARKED AS FOLLOWS: RESIN SOLUTION, UN1866, LTD. QTY., WITH A FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABEL ATTACHED. THERE WAS PROPER CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ACCOMPANIED THIS SHIPMENT. JON DONNED A CARTRIDGE MASK TO INVESTIGATE THE CAUSE OF THE ODOR. UPON INSPECTION, THE RESIN SOLUTION WAS PACKAGED INSIDE GLASS VIALS INSIDE FIBERBOARD BOXES. THERE WERE 11 INNER BOXES, 10 WERE 8 1/4 X 1 IN., RED AND WHITE FIBERBOARD WITH THE NAME OF THE PRODUCT PREPRINTED ON THEM. THREE OF THESE BOXES SHOWED SIGNS OF LEAKAGE. ONE INNER GLASS VIAL HAD BEEN CRACKED IN EACH BOX. NO INNER ABSORBANT MATERIAL WAS USED. THE REMAINING BOX WAS 8IN X12IN., BROWN FIBERBOARD UN 4G, MARKED AND LABELED FOR THE RESIN SOLUTION, WITH PREPRINTED ORIENTATION ARROWS. ONE INNER GLASS VIAL WAS CRACKED. NO INNER ABSORBANT WAS USED. THERE WAS RED PACKAGING PLACED INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS, PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM AND SENT ON TO DESTINATION. CLEAR OF SCENE: 0436.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, LOW SPECIFIC ACTIVITY (LSA-I) NON FISSILE OR FISSILE-EXCEPTED
column168: AT 1837 HOURS ON 4 MAY, 1994, E3, E7, DC2 AND HAZMAT WERE DISPATCHED TO A RADIATION INCIDENT AT THE INTERSECTION OF I-280 AND I-80. ARRIVING UNITS FOUND A 10,000 GALLON POLY TANK THAT HAD BEEN ON THE FLATBED SEMI TRAILER HAD STRUCK THE BRIDGE OVERPASS AND ROLLED DOWN THE INTERSTATE APPROX. 150 YARDS AND CAME TO REST IN THE DITCH SOUTH OF I-80. THE TANK WAS LABELED AS RADIOACTIVE AND APPEARED TO BE INTACT. DC2 REQUESTED THE RESPONSE OF #902 AND #906. THEY RESPONDED AND ARRIVED AT 1845. DC2 NOTIFIED IHP AND DOT AT 1857 FOR TRAFFIC CONTROL. 906 NOTIFIED DNR AT 1900 TO MAKE A PRELIMINARY REPORT. PER DNR, REP. FROM STATE DEPT. OF HEALTH WOULD BE ENROUTE FROM DES MOINES TO MONITOR FOR POSSIBLE CONTAMINATION WITH A ETA OF 0030. A CALL WAS MADE TO THE CONSIGNEE, DUANE ARNOLD ENERGY CENTER IN PALO, IA. WHO DISPATCHED TERRY WILKERSON TO THE SCENE FOR TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE. THE SHIPPING PAPERS WERE OBTAINED FROM THE DRIVER AND INDICATED THE TANKS WERE EMPTY, BUT CONTAMINATED WITH LSA RADIOACTIVITY. 902 AND 906 PERFORMED RAD MONITORING FROM THE COMMAND POST TO THE TANK IN THE DITCH AND DETECTED A MAX OF 75/M ON THE SURFACE OF THE TANK WITH NO SIGNIFICANT CONTAMINATION WITHIN A 5' RADIUS OF THE TANK. THE CONSIGNNE MADE ARRANGEMENTS FOR A CRANE TO RE-LOAD THE TANK ONTO THE TRAILER. IHP AND DOT CONTROLLED TRAFFIC WHILE THIS WAS ACCOMPLISHED AT APPROX. 2230 HOURS. THE TRUCK WAS ESCORTED BY IHP TO TRISM TRANSPORT AT 900 W. 76TH ST. DAVENPORT. AT APPROX. 0030, GEORGE JOHNS, AN ENVIRONMENTAL SPECIALIST FROM IA. DEPT. OF PUBLIC HEALTH ARRIVED FROM DES MOINES AND WAS ESCORTED TO THE SCENE BY 906 AND 902. JOHNS CHECKED THE SCENE FOR POSSIBLE RESIDUAL RADIOACTIVITY FROM THE OVERPASS TO THE TANKS' LOCATION AND DETECTED NO SIGNIFICANT CONTAMINATION. THIS CONFIRMED THE RESULTS OBTAINED BY 906 AND 902 WITH CDV INSTRAMENTS. A MR. DON BROOKSTRA FROM ILLINOIS-IOWA CLAIM SERVICE ARRIVED EARLY INTO THE INCIDENT TO REPRESENT THE INTEREST OF THE TRUCKING COMPANY, TRI-STATE MOTOR TRANSIT. ACCORDING TO THE ESCORT DRIVER, THE TRUCK DRIVER WAS WARNED OF THE OVERPASS HEIGHT VIA RADIO, BUT WAS UNABLE TO STOP IN TIME TO AVOID THE COLLISION. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THE TRIP FROM THE INCIDENT SCENE TO TRISM TOOK APPROX. 1.5 HOURS DUE TO THE EXCESSIVE HEIGHT OF THE TANKS AND THE NECESSITY TO PASS UNDER TWO MORE OVERPASSES ENROUTE. THE ONLY WAY TO MAKE THE LOAD CLEAR THE OVERPASSES WAS TO SHORTEN THE VEHICLE HEIGHT BY REMOVING THE AIR FROM THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE'S AIR RIDE SYSTEM WHICH ALLOWED CLEARANCE UNDER THE OVERPASSES BY APPROX. TWO INCHES. AFTER OUR ARRIVAL AT TRISM, THE REPS. FROM IDPH MONITORED THE TANKS FOR RAD LEAKAGE AND FOUND MODERATE LEVELS OF RADIOACTIVITY AT THE TANK SURFACES BUT NO LIQUID LEAKAGE. THIS CONFIRMED THAT WHILE THE TANK SUFFERED PHYSICAL DAMAGE, THE INTEGRITY REMAINED INTACT. INTERESTED PARTIES WERE OFFERED PICTURES TAKEN BY THE HAZMAT TEAM OF THE INCIDENT. ONE SET WILL BE SENT TO EACH OF THE FOLLOWING:

column168: OUR DRIVER CLAUDIE CHILDS FOUND A DRIP ORIGINATING FROM THE END GATE OF HIS TRAILER ON MAY 27TH., DURING A TIRE AND LOAD INSPECTION.  HE WAS AN EXIT NEAR SALISAW, OK.  HE IMMEDIATELY PLACED PLASTIC SHEETING ON THE GROUND AND CALLED DISPATCH.  HE WAS DIRECTED TO REMAIN THERE, SINCE HE DID NOT HAVE ANY ABSORBENT TO DRY THE LIQUID INSIDE HIS TRAILER.  HE PLACED A TOWEL AT THE END GATE WHICH PREVENTED ANY MORE LIQUID FROM HITTING THE GROUND AND PLACED SHEET ON THE GROUND AS A PRECAUTION.  I WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SITUATION AND DIRECTED OUR RESPONSE TRAILER TO THE SCENE TO ASSIST THE DRIVER.  OUR RESPONSE CREW PLACED OIL DRY IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. THEY PLACED A SMALL AMOUNT OF ABSORBENT ON THE PLASTIC AND ON THE GROUND WHERE THE LEAK OCCURRED.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL, ABSORBENT AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF CONTAMINATED GRAVEL WAS REMOVED AND PLACED INSIDE THE TRAILER. LESS THAN SIX OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND.  THE DRIVER'S EFFORTS HAD CONTAINED THE SPILL.  THIS LOAD ORIGINATED FROM FARMLAND INDUSTRIES IN COFFEYVILLE, KS AND WAS IN ROUTE TO RINECO CHEMICAL INDUSTRIES, HASKELL, AR.  I CONTACTED BOTH FARMLAND INDUSTRIES AND RINCO CONCERNING THIS SITUATION.  COPIES OF THESE LETTERS ARE ENCLOSED.  DUE TO THE RECENT INCREASE OF DRIPS, FROM END DUMP LOAD, I HAVE IMPLEMENTED NEW POLICY AIMED AT REDUCING SPILLS AND CONTAMINATION.  THE NEW PROCEDURES ARE: 1.  WARNING LANGUAGE IN END DUMP BID PROPOSALS STATING THE MATERIAL MUST BE DRY.  2.  DRIVERS WEEKLY NOTICE WARNING DRIVERS TO INSPECT LOADS WHEN LOADING AND BEFORE ACCEPTING MATERIAL PREVIOUSLY LOADED IN AND END DUMP FOR DAMP OR WET MATERIAL UNSUITABLE FOR TRANSPORT.  DRIVERS KNOWINGLY FAILING TO DO THIS MAY FACE TERMINATION.   SEE ENCLOSED COPY.  3. INSPECTION OF ALL LOADS ARRIVING AT OUR TERMINALS.  4.  A LETTER, INCLUDING A COPY OF THIS REPORT, IS SENT TO ALL GENERATORS ADVISING OF THE NATURE OF ANY SPILL AND REQUESTING THEIR EFFORTS TO PREVENT A REOCCURENCE. THIS FOLLOWS UP A PHONE NOTIFICATION, AT TIME OF SPILL, AND CAUSES GENERATOR TO CONSIDER CONSEQUENCES AND COSTS OF SHIPPING MATERIAL NOT SUITABLE (WET) FOR TRANSPORT IN AN END DUMP.

column42: ALKYLAMINES, N.O.S. OR POLYALKYLAMINES, N.O.S. CORROSIVE
column168: ON 5/24/94 AT 0249, SORT SUPERVISOR BILL MINK REPORTED A SPILL INSIDE DOOR B-8 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DR, WILMINGTON, OH 45177.  THE SPILL WAS REPORTED COMING FROM A BLACK STEEL DRUM WITH AN ODOR OF GLUE, 2 EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR OF GLUE, 2 EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR.  HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR FRAN VANCE AND P/T HAZMAT SPILL TECHNICIAN ADDIE CAMPTON RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A BLACK STEEL, 5 GALLON DRUM LEAKING LIQUID AROUND THE FRICTION TYPE CLOSURE.  NO ODOR PRESENT.  THERE WAS NO INDICATION ON THE DRUM AS TO ITS CONTENTS.  THE LIQUID WAS PH'D, NEUTRAL READING.  DUE TO THE 2 EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT, THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS THEN PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM AND HELD IN THE HAZMAT SORT FACILITY FOR A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 0302.  UPON FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE DRUM, THE LEAKING LIQUID WAS NOW EMITTING A GLUE TYPE ODOR, ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE MASKS WERE DONNED AND INSPECTION CONTINUED.  THE LIQUID WAS CLEAR YELLOW IN COLOR WITH A PH OF 11.  THIS PH READING CAME ONLY AFTER THE PH PAPER WAS LEFT ON THE LIQUID FOR APPROXIMATELY 2 MINUTES.  A MESSAGE WAS SENT TO THE SHIPPER REQUESTING A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET ON THE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM.  UPON RECEIPT OF THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET, THE CONTENTS WERE FOUND TO BE: ALKYLAMINES, N.O.S., 8, UN2735.

AT 1115 HOURS ON MAY 17TH IN FRONTIER YARD, CONDUCTOR G.T. MROWINSKI OBSERVED PRODUCT "VENTING" FROM PROX 14261 AS HE WAS SWITCHING CARS. SHORTLY THEREAFTER MROWINSKI FELT AN IRRITATION TO THE SKIN OF HIS FACE; DR. GRIPPI OF HEALTH WORKS CLINIC DIAGNOSED "MILD CHEMICAL CONJUNCTIVITIS" AND PRESCIBED SKIN CREAM AND EYE DROPS.  A RESPONSE TEAM FROM MARSULEX DISCOVERED THAT THE FILL HATCH COVER GASKET WAS BROKEN IN HALF.  THEY CHANGED THE GASKET AND WASHED THE CAR WITH SODA ASH SOLUTION.
DRIVE HAD COMPLETED THE DELIVERY TO THE HOME WHEN HE TURNED AROUND HE SAW A SMALL SPRAY OF OIL COMING OUT OF THE HOSE.  A CLEAN UP CREW WAS CALLED IN TO REMOVE THE CONTAMINATED SOIL.

column168: ON WEDNESDAY, 5/18/94, REGIONAL MANAGER CTS, T.M. ROBINSON, RECEIVED A CALL FROM UPRR CAR FOREMAN, SETTEGAST YARD, MR. ALGER N. PARROTT. PARROTT ADVISED THAT THIS CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING A SMALL STREAM OF PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE CAP. THE LEAKING PRODUCT WAS EVAPORATING AS IT HIT THE BALLAST. THE SHIPPER, PHIBRO ENERGY USA, HAD BEEN NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED PERSONNEL TO THE YARD. THE TOP OPERATED, BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS CLOSED, AND THIS SECURED THE CAR FROM LEAKING. ADDITIONALLY, THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE CAP GASKET WAS FOUND TO BE DEFECTIVE AND WAS REPLACED AT THIS TIME. THE CAR WAS ONCE AGAIN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ON TO DESTINATION.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: AT 0545 HRS CDT, UPRR EMPLOYEES AT NEFF YARD IN KANSAS CITY REPORTED APPARENT LEAKAGE FROM TANK CAR UCLX 30088. INSPECTION BY SAHM KEN DECHANT DISCLOSED A VERY SMALL VOLUME OF PRODUCT APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN RELEASED, ALL FROM THE CONNECTION BETWEEN THE MANWAY NOZZLE AND THE MANWAY COVER PLATE. THIS FITTING IS SECURED BY MEANS OF 20 BOLTS, AND IS EQUIPPED WITH TOP AND BOTTOM SEGMENTAL WASHERS TO REINFORCE THE CONNECTION. LEAKAGE HAD COME FROM BENEATH ONE OF THE SEGMENTAL WASHER SECTIONS, ALONG THE AREA SECURED BY 3 ADJACENT BOLTS. AT THE TIME OF INSPECTION, WITH AN AMBIENT TEMPERATURE OF 80 DEGREES F., A SLIGHT VAPOR RELEASE WAS AUDIBLE FROM THE AREA OF THESE BOLTS, WHICH INCREASED WITH THE TIGHTENING OF THE CENTER BOLT OF THE THREE. LOOSENING OF THIS BOLT DIMINISHED THE VAPOR RELEASE, AND TIGHTENING OF THE TWO SURROUNDINGS BOLTS STOPPED IT COMPLETELY. TWO ADDITIONAL BOLTS, ADJACENT TO THIS AREA WERE ALSO FOUND TO BE LOOSE, AND WERE TIGHTENED TO FURTHER SECURE THE FITTING. NO OTHER EXCEPTIONS WERE NOTED, AND THE FRANGIBLE DISC WAS FOUND TO BE INTACT. CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AT 1445 HRS. FOLLOW-UP INSPECTION WAS CONDUCTED ON 5/17/94 AT COUNCIL BLUFFS, IA., WITH NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE FOUND. DETAILS OF THIS INCIDENT WERE FUNTISHED TO THE SHIPPER, TO ALLOW FOR COMPLETE INSPECTION OF THE MANWAY COVER PLATE ASSEMBLY FOR POSSIBLE CORROSION DAMAGE, PRIOR TO THE CAR BEING RELOADED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER CHEM. TRANS. SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED THAT A TRAILER AT THE U.P. MOTOR FREIGHT FACILITY WAS LEAKING FROM THE REAR DOORS. THE TRAILER WAS SET TO STORAGE LOT #6 AND ISOLATED PENDING AN INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER INSPECTED THE TRAILER, WHICH WAS NOT PLACARDED AND SHIPPED AS FAK. HE NOTED THAT THE LEAKING MATERIAL WAS FROM A SINGLE CARTON AT THE REAR DOOR WHICH CONTAINED BATTERY FLUID. THE CARTON CONTAINED (4) EACH SMALLER CARTONS WITH POLY BLADDERS HOLDING THE FLUID. THE CARTON HAD BEEN PLACED BETWEEN THE REAR DOOR AND A LARGE MECHANICAL PUMP. DUE TO A LOAD SHIFT AND NO BLOCKING/BRACING, THE PUMP CRUSHED THE CARTON AGAINST THE REAR DOOR OF THE TRAILER. A LARGE (24") GEAR HAD ALSO EMBEDDED THE CARTON, HOWEVER, IT IS NOT KNOWN WHERE THE GEAR HAD ALSO EMBEDDED THE CARTON, HOWEVER, IT IS NOT KNOWN WHERE THE GEAR WAS ORIGINALLY LOADED IN THE TRAILER. THE CARTONS CONTAINING THE BATTERY FLUID WERE PROPERLY MARKDED AND LABELED. THE CARTONS WERE DOT12B65, #278, 350 POUND TEST, MANUFACTURED BY MACMILLAN BLOEDEL CONTAINER, JERSEY CITY, N.J., SHIPPED BY ITT FLUID TECHNOLOGY CORP., 1150 TENNESSEE AVE., CINCINNATI, OHIO, 45229, REFERENCE ORDER NUMBERS 0624 & 95232. THREE OF THE FOUR BLADDERS WERE RUPTURED, RELEASING THE CONTENTS. THE ONE GOOD BLADDER WAS PLACED INTO A POLY BAG TO PREVENT ADDITIONAL RELEASE OF THE ACID. THE RESIDUE WAS ALSO PLACED INTO POLY BAGS TO LIMIT FURTHER CONTAMINATION. AS THERE WAS NO FREE STANDING LIQUID IN THE TRAILER, THE CONSIGNEE TRANSPORTED THE TRAILER TO THEIR DOCK.

AFTER INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE POLYLINER IN WHAT APPEARED TO BE A RE-CONDITIONED DRUM FAILED. PRODUCT CALLED ETS 900 (ACETIXYSILANE) WEPT FROM TWO HOLES DRILLED NEAR THE BOTTOM ON THE SIDES OF THE DRUM IMPACTING THE SURROUNDING DRUMS AND THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. ALL THE DRUMS, AND FLOOR WERE CLEANED AND A TOTAL OF FOUR, ONE LEAKING DRUM AND THREE SUSPECT DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED. THESE DRUMS HAD POLYLINERS THAT WERE CRIMPED ROLLED AS PART OF THE REMOVEABLE HEAD ON THE DRUM THUS MAKING THE HEADS, WHEN THE DRUMS WERE LOADED, NOT REMOVEABLE. THIS MADE IT IMPOSSIBLE TO INSPECT THE SUSPECT LINERS IN THE OTHER THREE OVERPACKED DRUMS. MATERIAL WAS NOT DECLARED ON BILLING PROVIDED TO UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD (COPY ATTACHED).

column168: 8:00AM - BILL KENNEDY IS NOTIFIED BY THE DRIVER DALE GUINN, THAT DURING THE PROCESS OF LOADING A TARPED ROLLOFF BOX ONTO THE ROLL-OFF TRAILER, THE BOX HAD FLIPPED OFF ONTO IT'S SIDE ON THE GROUND. THE MATERIAL HAD EXITED OUT OF THE BOX ONTO THE CANVAS TARP. THE MATERIAL WAS A SOLID (TYPICAL FILTER CAKE WITH NO OBVIOUS WATER.) THERE WAS NO IMMEDIATE HARM TO THE ENVIRONMENT OR THE HEALTH OF ANY INDIVIDUAL BASED ON HIS OBSERVATIONS. THE DRIVER GIVES A SITE CONTACT, TOM MRAZ. 8:30AM - DAVID CONTACTS TOM MRAZ. MR. MRAZ EXPRESSES HIS DESIRE FOR ENVIRITE TO CONTACT A PROFESSIONAL RESPONSE COMPANY, TO ASSIST IN THE CLEANUP, WHICH ENVIRITE AGREED WITH AND PROCEEDED TO EXECUTE.  9:00AM - SEVERAL RESPONSE COMPANIES ARE CONTACTED BEFORE LOCATING FERGUSON ENVIRONMENTAL & RESPONSE IN BOWLING GREEN, KY. FERGUSON IS ABLE TO RESPOND WITHIN THE TIME FRAME NEEDED. 12:00 - FERGUSON'S CREW HAS ARRIVED AND THE CLEANUP BEGIN WITH A FEW EQUIPMENT PROBLEMS. FLAT TIRES ON THE RENTED BOBCAT.  3:00 - THE CLEANUP IS IN THE FINAL STAGES. FERGUSON HAS LOADED THE MATERIAL FROM THE TARP INTO THE EMPTY BOX SPOTTED BY THE DRIVER. THE BOX ON ITS SIDE IS THEN RIGHTED AND VISUALLY INSPECTED WITH NO APPARENT DAMAGE. FERGUSON PROCEEDS TO SCRAPE AND CLEAN THE TARP AND AREA AS REQUESTED BY KEN DEC. 4:30 - CLEANUP IS COMPLETED TO THE SATISFACTION OF KEN DEC WITH NO APPARENT MATERIAL ON THE GROUND. FERGUSON IS GIVEN AUTHORIZATION TO LEAVE THE SCENE BY DAVID AFTER RECEIVING CONFIRMATION FROM KEN DEC THAT THE CLEANUP IS COMPLETED. THE ENVIRITE DRIVER LEAVES WITHOUT A LOAD. ARRANGEMENTS ARE MAKE WITH MR. KIDD TO PICK UP THE LOADED BOX SATURDAY MORNING.  THAT THE DRIVERS NEED TO CONTINUE TO PERFORM PROPER PRE-TRIP INSPECTIONS. THAT THE CONTINGENCY SPILL PLAN IS UPDATED WITH ADDITIONAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANIES. THAT ALL ENVIRITE DRIVERS RECEIVE UPDATED TRAINING WHICH ALLOWS THE INDIVIDUAL DRIVER TO MAKE THE DECISION NOT TO LOAD IF CONDITIONS ARE UNSAFE. THAT THE DRIVER, INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT, RECEIVE ADDITIONAL DOCUMENTED TRAINING ON THE OPERATIONS OF ROLL-OFF EQUIPMENT. THAT THIS TRAINING BE COMPLETED BEFORE BEING DISPATCHED AGAIN TO HANDLE A ROOL-OFF PICKUP. THAT ALL OF THE ENVIRITE TRANSPORTATION PERSONNEL INVOLVED MEET TO DISCUSS THE RESPONSE AND HOW TO IMPROVE FOR THE FUTURE. THIS MEETING WILL NEED TO BE CONDUCTED WITHIN THIRTY (30) DAYS OF THE INCIDENT. THAT D.O.T. FORM F5800.1 IS COMPLETED AND MAILED TO THE PROPER AUTHORITIES AND THE CUSTOMER BY JUNE 13TH.  THE ROLL-OFF TRAILER USED HAD ALL OF THE CURRENT REQUIRED ANNUAL INSPECTIONS. AFTER INSPECTING THE TRAILER THE INITIAL CONJECTURE IS THAT THE DRIVER FAILED TO LOAD THE BOX ONTO THE RAILS PROPERLY. THAT THE VISUAL INSPECTIONS WILL BE INCREASED TO QUARTERLY INSPECTIONS BEGINNING IN JUNE, THE END OF THE 2ND QUARTER. THAT AN OUTSIDE VENDOR IS USED, AS WELL AS, AN IN HOUSE INSPECTIONS TO ASSURE CERTIFICATION. THAT THE MAINTENANCE PROGRAM IS REVIEWED. THIS REPORT WILL NEED TO BE COMPLETED BY JUNE 15TH. UPON REACHING THE TANK, THEY DISCOVERED THE VALVE HAD BEEN KNOCKED OPEN.  THE HAZMAT TEAM SECURED THE VALVE AND REMOVED THE TANK TO CHECK FOR ANY DAMAGE.  THERE WAS NONE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT NEUTRALIZED ALL SPILLED PRODUCT PER THEIR REPRESENTATIVE, BILL DOWNEY.  THE SHIPPER (MOONEY CHEMICAL, RICK WALBURN) AUTHORIZED RETURN OF THE TOTE TO THEM.

RODNEY SCHROER, A DISTRIBUTION EMPLOYEE, WAS MOVING A CASE OF CHLOROFORM ON THE LOADING DOCK IN PREPARATION FOR LOADING A TRAILER.  THE BOX SLIPPED FROM HIS HANDS AND FELL FROM A WAIST HIGH CARRYING POSITION TO THE FLOOR. RODNEY SHIFTED THE BOX AND DISCOVERED CHLOROFORM LEAKING OUT ONTO THE FLOOR.  HE IMMEDIATELY SIGNALED HIS SUPERVISOR, TIM SIEBENMORGEN, WHO CAME OVER TO INVESTIGATE THE SPILL.  IN THE COURSE OF THE "INVESTIGATION", BOTH TIM AND RODNEY WERE EXPOSED TO THE CHEMICAL.  WHEN TIM NOTICED THE CHOLOFORM ODOR, HE EVACUATED THE FACILITY (3 PEOPLE), AND BEGAN THE PROCESS OF CALLING EMERGENCY CONTACTS.  RODNEY WAS INSTRUCTED TO WASH HIS ARMS WITH SOAP AND WATER AS HE WAS SPLASHED AS HE AND TIM "INVESTIGATED" THE SPILL.  TIM TRANSCRIBED TWO OF THE PHONE NUMBERS FROM THE EMERGENCY CALL LIST INCORRECTLY SO THAT HE WAS UNABLE TO GET THROUGH TO THE LOCAL CONTACTS.  HE THEN TELEPHONED CORPORATE QARA WHO INSTRUCTED HIM TO CALL THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER.  AT THIS TIME, TIM CALLED 911.  THE PRODUCT WAS DROPPED AT APPROXIMATELY 0300 ON MAY 26, 1994.  TIM EVACUATED THE FACILITY AT  0305.  HE DIALED 911 AT 0345 AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED WITHIN FIVE MINUTES.  PARAMEDICS EXAMINED RODNEY AND DETERMINED THAT HE DID NOT SUFFER FROM ANY REACTIONS TO HIS EXPOSURE. THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM CLEARED THE CHLOROFORM CONTAINERS FROM THE LOADING DOCK AND THE SPLIT CHEMICAL WAS ALLOWED TO EVAPORATE.  WE HAVE INSTITUATED FURTHER TRAINING IN PRODUCT HANDLING, SPILL RESPONSE AND WE ARE PREPARING AN UPDATED PHONE LIST.

column168: AT 10:45 HARRY EVERETT CALLED TO REPORT A HAZARDOUS CORROSIVE LEAKING PKG. HE SAID THERE WAS NO SPILLAGE AND FROM THE 5 PART FORM IDENTIFIED AMMONIUM HYDROXIDE.  I INFORMED HIM NOT TO MOVE PKG AND I WOULD GET TO WHERE HE WAS.  HE WAS INSTRUCTED NOT TO ENTER THE CAR.  RICK AND MYSELF TOOK ALL NECESSARY PPE USING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE GUIDE AS A GUIDE AND DROVE TO NEW IPSWICH MARK GAMBESKI FOLLOWED IN A CAR.  AT THE SITE WE DETERMINED THERE WAS NO SPILLAGE, NOR WERE THERE FUMES PRESENT. WE CONTAINED THE PKG IN A SPILL BUCKET WRAPPED IN SEALED IN A DMP BAG WITH VERMICULITE AND SPEEDI DRY AND TRANSFERRED TO P-500 WHERE MARK TRANSPORTED IT BACK TO NASHUA.  RICK AND I DETERMINED THAT LESS THAN 6 OUNCES HAD BEEN LOST.  WE DISPOSED OF DAMAGED BOX USING DMP PROCEDURE AND RETURNED THE PRODUCT TO SHIPPER AFTER SECURING CAP.  TOTAL CLEANUP AND DECONTAMINATION WAS COMPLETED AT 2:45 PM.

column168: H. KREVIT DRIVER WAS SUSPENDED AND FINED FOR FAILURE TO FOLLOW UNLOADING PROCEDURE.  LT. DUFFY AND I ARRIVED AT JOHNSON MEMORIAL HOSPITAL ROOM 203, WHERE I MET AND INTERVIEW KEITH NUTTER WHO IS EMPLOYED AT THE WATER POLLUTION CONTROL PLANT AND IS CLASSIFIED AN ATTENDANT #1.  NUTTER STATED THAT AT APPROXIMATELY 7:40 AM HE WAS AT WORK AND WENT WITH OTHER EMPLOYEES TO THE REAR YARD WHERE A MICHAEL'S CATERING TRUCK HAD LAST ARRIVED. NUTTER STATED PRESENT AT THE TRUCK WAS MIKE MERRILL, MIKE NUTTER, AND HANK ANDERSON AND MIKE, THE OWNER OF MICHAEL'S CATERING.  A TRANKER TRUCK PULLED INTO THE YARD AND NUTTER BELIEVES THAT HANK ANDERSON STATED THAT THE FERRIC TRUCK HAD ARRIVED.  FERRIC BEING A REFERENCE TO FERRIC CHLORIDE.  THE TRUCK OPERATOR ALLEDGEDLY APPROACHED THE GROUP AND NUTTER TOLD HIM TO BACK HIS TRUCK UP NEAR THE RAMP TO UNLOAD.  NUTTER DID NOT NOTICE ANY MARKINGS INDICATING THE TRUCK'S CONTENT BUT HE WAS NOT LOOKING FOR ANY AT THAT TIME.  THE TRUCK OPERATOR NEVER TOLD ANYONE IN THE GROUP WHAT HE WAS CARRYING ON THE TRUCK AND NOBODY ASKED HIM.   NO PAPERWORK WAS PRESENTED TO ANYONE INDICATING THAT THE LOAD WAS FERRIC CHLORIDE.  THE TRUCKER BACKED TO THE RAMP AND THE EMPLOYEES WENT INTO THE BREAK ROOM TO START THEIR BREAK.  A FEW MINUTES LATER THE TRUCKER ENTERED THE BREAK ROOM AND ASKED WHAT FCI MEANT AS IT WAS WRITTEN NEAR THE FILL PIPE.  EITHER MIKE DUDEK OR MIKE MERRILL TOLD HIM IT WAS ACTUALLY PCL AND MEANT FERRIC CHLORIDE.  NUTTER STATED THE TRUCKER LOOKED "DUMFOUNDED" AND WALKED BACK OUTSIDE.  NUTTER ACCOMPANIED HIM TO THE RAMP AREA AND NOTICED THAT TANKER HAD BEEN CONNECTED TO THE FILL PIPE FOR FERRIC CHLORIDE.  HE TOLD THE TRUCKER THAT HE WAS CONNECTED TO THE FERRIC CHLORIDE TANK THEN HE RETURNED TO THE BREAK ROOM.  A FEW MINUTES LATER NUTTER STATES THAT THE TRUCKER AGAIN ENTERED THE BREAK ROOM AND SAID THAT SOMETHING SMELLED FUNNY.  THEY THEN EVACUATED THE BUILDING.  NUTTER ALSO STATED THAT WHEN ORIGINALLY APPROACHED BY THE TRUCKER, HE WAS SIMPLY TOLD THAT HE HAD 4000 POUNDS TO DELIVER.  HE NEVER IDENTIFIED HIS LOAD.  NUTTER STATED HE NEVER SAW ANY PAPERWORK IDENTIFYING THE LOAD.  I ARRIVED AT THE WATER POLLUTION CONTROL PLANT AND INTERVIEW HANK ANDERSON, ACTING PLANT SUPERINTENDANT.  ANDER STATED THAT HE WAS IN THE YARD AROUND 7:30 AM WHEN HE SAW A TANKER PULL INTO THE YARD.  HE ASSUMED THE TANKER CONTAINED FERRIC CHLORIDE AND YELLED TO THE EMPLOYEES AT THE CATERING TRUCK THAT THE FERRIC HAD ARRIVED.  HANK BOUGHT A BAGEL AND ENTERED HIS OFFICE.  A FEW MINUTES LATER NUTTER ASKED HIM HOW MUCH FERRIC CHLORIDE WAS IN THE TANK.  ANDERSON CHECKED THE SHEETS AND TOLD HIM THAT THEY WERE OUT.   NUTTER LEFT.  A FEW MINUTES LASTER HE HEARD MIKE DUDEK AND MIKE MERRILL YELLING TO EVACUATE THE BUILDING. ANDERSON DID SO AND THEN REENTERED IT TO HELP VENTILATE IT.  HE WENT TO THE REAR YARD AND THEN ENTERED THE BUILDING AGAIN TO ACTIVATE THE LARGE EXHAUST FANS.  DURING HIS FIRST EXIT FROM THE BUILDING HE CONTACTED EMERGENCY SERVICES.  WHEN ASKED HOW

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFTY, WAS NOTIFIED BY ITS RAMP PERSONNEL THAT A RAMP DRIVER REPORTED A CONTAINER, DSLU 450629, IN THE WESTBOUND DTRAILER STORAGE LOT #9, LEAKING SOME UNKNOWN SUBSTANCE FROM THE REAR DOORS.  MANAGERCOOPER INSPECTED THE CONTAINER AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM ONE 55-GALLON DRUM CONTAINING NAPTHA.  AS APL WAS THE SHIPPER OF RECORD, THEY WERE CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF DOMESTIC SHIPMENT AND CONTACTED THE SHIPPER (DSL), WHO ARRANGED TO HAVE THE CONTENTS INSPECTED BY A MARINE SURVEYOR.  THE SURVEYOR VARIFIED THE LEAKING CONTENTS AND RECOMMENDED THE CONTENTS BE TRANSLOADED .  DSL CONTRACTED ILSC TO RECOOP THE LADING, WHICH COMPLETED ON FRIDAY JUNE 3, 1994.  A SINGLE 55-GALLON DRUM OF NAPTHA WAS REMOVED FROM THE CONTAINER, PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK, AND DELIVERED TO A DSL WAREHOUSE IN LONG BEACH FOR DISPOSITION.  THE CONTAINER WAS THEN RELEASED TO DSL FOR DELIVERY ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  UPON CONTACTING DSL, WAS ADVISED THE DAMAGED DRUM IS BEING RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  AFTER NUMEROUS REQUESTS, NEITHER DSL NOR FERRO CORP. HAS BEEN ABLE TO PROVIDE INFORMATION ON THE SPECIFICATION MARKINGS FROM THE DRUM.  THEREFORE, NO FURTHER ATTEMPTS TO SECURE INFORMATION WILL BE MADE.

AT 02:30 A CALL ABOUT A LIQUID DAMAGE ON THE GREAT NECK SLIDE WAS MADE TO THE DMP AREA.  J PARRINO RESPONDED TO THE CALL WITH THE SPILL CART.  THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SPILL TUB AND BROUGHT BACK TO THE DMP AREA.  THE LEAKAGE WAS ABSORBED BY THE OUTSIDE CARTON, THE AREA WAS CLEANED WITH SPEEDI-DRY AND SOLUSORB.  THE CONTAMINATED PORTION OF THE DAMAGE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE UPS DAMAGED MATERIALS PROGRAM.  THE SCBA WAS NOT USED BECAUSE THERE WERE NO FUMES OR ODORS PRESENT.  NO INJURIES OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF OF THIS DAMAGE.  INFORMATION ABOUT THIS DAMAGE FORWARDED TO SORT MANAGER FOR REVIEW.
